 \u2013 WW1 and WW2 |date= |accessdate=6 February 2020|work=[[Imperial War Museum]]}}</ref><ref name=HPtal>{{cite web |author=|url=https://historypoints.org/index.php?page=talgarth-war-memorial |title=Talgarth war memorial|date=|accessdate=6 February 2020|work=historypoints.org}}</ref> \n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Welshpool ==\n{{Public art header|show_architect=no|show_material=yes|show_dimensions=yes|show_owner=no|show_wikidata=yes}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Powis Castle 2016 054.jpg\n| commonscat =\n| subject = ''[[Hercules]]''\n| location = [[Powis Castle]], [[Welshpool]] \n| date = {{circa|1692|sortbale=yes}}\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = [[Andries Carpenti\u00e8re]]\n| type = Statue\n| material = Lead \n| dimensions =\n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata =\n| notes =<ref name=\"Pevsner\"/> \n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Powis Castle 2016 004.jpg\n| commonscat =\n| subject = ''Fame''\n| location = [[Powis Castle]], [[Welshpool]] \n| date = {{circa|1705|sortbale=yes}}\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = [[Andries Carpenti\u00e8re]]\n| type = Statue of a winged female on horseback\n| material = Lead statue on a stone base\n| dimensions =\n| designation = Grade II*\n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata =\n| notes =<ref name=\"Pevsner\"/><ref>{{cadw|num=16785 |desc=Statue of Fame in entrance courtyard at Powis Castle |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>  \n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Lead statues on terrace wall, Powis Castle - geograph.org.uk - 331289.jpg\n| commonscat =\n| subject = Shepherds and shepherdesses\n| location = [[Powis Castle]], [[Welshpool]] \n| date = {{circa|1705|sortable=yes}}\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = Studio of [[John Nost]]\n| type = Four statues\n| material = Lead \n| dimensions =\n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata =\n| notes =<ref name=\"Pevsner\"/> \n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Y Trallwng Welshpool 10.JPG\n| commonscat =\n| subject = War memorial\n| location = St Mary's [[Welshpool]] \n| date = 1923\n| show_artist= \n| artist = \n| type = Pillar cross & wall with plaques\n| material = Stone\n| dimensions =\n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata =\n| notes = <ref name=HPwelsh>{{cite web |author=|url= https://historypoints.org/index.php?page=welshpool-war-memorial|title=Welshpool war memorial|date=|accessdate=27 January 2020|work=historypoints.org}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Ystradgynlais==\n{{Public art header|show_architect=no|show_material=yes|show_dimensions=yes|show_owner=no|show_wikidata=yes}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Ystradgynlais War Memorial, January 2020.jpg\n| commonscat =\n| subject = War memorial\n| location = Gorsedd Park, [[Ystradgynlais]]\n| date = {{circa|1970s|sortable=yes}}\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist =   \n| type = Memorial\n| material = Stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation =\n| coordinates= \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = Re-landscaped and additional plaques added in 2016.<ref name=HPystrad>{{cite web |author=|url=https://historypoints.org/index.php?page=ystradgynlais-war-memorial |title=Ystradgynlais war memorial|date=|accessdate=27 January 2020|work=historypoints.org}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Gorsedd Stones in Ystradgynlais - geograph.org.uk - 4975242.jpg\n| commonscat =\n| subject = [[Gorsedd stones]]\n| location = Gorsedd Park, [[Ystradgynlais]]\n| date = 1954\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist =   \n| type = Stone circle\n| material = Stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation =\n| coordinates= \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = Erected to mark the 1954 [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]] \n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Remembering the Miners, Diamond Park, Ystradgynlais, Wales.jpg\n| commonscat =\n| subject = ''Remembering the Miners''\n| location = Diamond Park, [[Ystradgynlais]]\n| date = 2014\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist =   \n| type = Sculpture\n| material = Stone and slate\n| dimensions = \n| designation =\n| coordinates= \n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = Situated on the site of a former colliery.<ref name=HPdiamond>{{cite web |author=|url=https://historypoints.org/index.php?page=diamond-park-ystradgynlais|title=Diamond Park, Ystradgynlais|date=|accessdate=26 January 2020|work=historypoints.org}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Powys}}\n{{UK public art}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Public art in Powys}}\n[[Category:Lists of public art in Wales|Powys]]\n[[Category:Powys]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: Foundary \u2192 Foundry, vistor \u2192 visitor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_public_art_in_Powys"}
{"title_page": "Big Ben", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Bell within the clock tower at the Palace of Westminster in London, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Elizabeth Tower\n| native_name         = \n| alternate_names     = Big Ben\n| image               = Clock Tower - Palace of Westminster, London - May 2007.jpg\n| caption             = \n| building_type       = [[Clock tower]]\n| architectural_style = [[Gothic Revival]]\n| structural_system   = \n| location            = [[Westminster]], London, England\n| owner               = \n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|51.5007|-0.1245|display=inline,title|region:GB_type:landmark}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = {{start date and age|df=yes|31 May 1859}}\n| height              = {{convert|96|m|ft}}\n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 11\n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = [[Augustus Pugin]]\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n}}\n'''Big Ben''' is the nickname for the Great Bell of the [[striking clock]] at the north end of the [[Palace of Westminster]] in London<ref name=wbfbb>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/bigben.htm| title=The Story of Big Ben|publisher=Whitechapel Bell Foundry| accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> and is usually [[Metonymy|extended to refer]] to both the clock and the [[clock tower]].<ref name=BigBenCOD>{{cite book| last=Fowler| first=H. W.| authorlink=Henry Watson Fowler| others=First edited by H. W. Fowler and F. G. Fowler| title=The Concise Oxford dictionary of current English| edition=Sixth| year=1976| page=[https://archive.org/details/conciseoxforddic00syke/page/95 95]| publisher=[[Clarendon Press]]| isbn=978-0-19-861121-9| quote=Big Ben, great bell, clock, and tower, of Houses of Parliament| url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/conciseoxforddic00syke/page/95}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_2016_04_26\">{{cite web| title=Big Ben 'bongs' to be silenced for \u00a329m refurbishment|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36138203| work=BBC News| publisher=BBC| accessdate=26 April 2016| date=26 April 2016}}</ref> The official name of the tower in which Big Ben is located was originally the '''Clock Tower''', but it was renamed '''Elizabeth Tower''' in 2012 to mark the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]].\n\nThe tower was designed by [[Augustus Pugin]] in a [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-Gothic style]]. When completed in 1859, its clock was the largest and most accurate four-faced striking and chiming clock in the world.<ref>{{cite news| title=Why is Big Ben falling silent?|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20160704-the-big-ben-renovation-and-how-the-clock-works| last=Excell| first=Jon| publisher=BBC| date=5 July 2016}}</ref> The tower stands {{convert|315|ft|m|0}} tall, and the climb from ground level to the belfry is 334 steps. Its base is square, measuring {{convert|39|ft|m|0}} on each side. Dials of the clock are {{convert|23|ft|m|1}} in diameter. On 31 May 2009, celebrations were held to mark the tower's 150th anniversary.<ref name=\"parliament.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART16| title=Join in the anniversary celebrations| publisher=UK Parliament| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202121929/http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART16| archivedate=2 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBig Ben is the largest of the tower's five bells and weighs {{convert|13.5|LT|t ST|1|abbr=off|lk=on}}.<ref name=wbfbb /> It was the largest bell in the United Kingdom for 23 years. The origin of the bell's nickname is open to question; it may be named after Sir [[Benjamin Hall, 1st Baron Llanover|Benjamin Hall]], who oversaw its installation, or [[heavyweight]] [[boxing]] champion [[Benjamin Caunt]]. Four [[quarter bells]] chime at 15, 30 and 45 minutes past the hour and just before Big Ben tolls on the hour. The clock uses its original Victorian mechanism, but an electric motor can be used as a backup.\n\nThe tower is a [[Culture of the United Kingdom|British cultural icon]] recognised all over the world. It is one of the most prominent symbols of the United Kingdom and parliamentary democracy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/426|title=Palace of Westminster and Westminster Abbey including Saint Margaret's Church| publisher=[[UNESCO]]}}</ref> and it is often used in the [[establishing shot]] of films set in London.<ref>{{cite news| title=Big Ben in films and popular culture|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/10525651/Big-Ben-in-films-and-popular-culture.html| newspaper=The Daily Telegraph| date=8 November 2016}}</ref> The clock tower has been part of a [[Grade I listed building]] since 1970 and a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] since 1987.\n\nOn 21 August 2017, a four-year schedule of renovation works began on the tower, which are to include the addition of a [[elevator|lift]]. There are also plans to re-glaze and repaint the clock dials. With a few exceptions, such as New Year's Eve and [[Remembrance Sunday]], the bells are to be silent until the work is completed in 2021.\n\n== Tower ==\n=== Origin ===\n[[File:Gary O'Donoghue on the Elizabeth Tower.ogg|thumb|Audio description of the tower by [[Gary O'Donoghue]]]]\nElizabeth Tower, previously called the Clock Tower<!--Not St Stephen's -- see [[Talk:Big Ben/Archive 2#St Stephen's Tower]]--> but more popularly known as Big Ben,<ref name=BBC_2016_04_26 /><ref name=\"parliament.uk\" /> was raised as a part of [[Charles Barry]]'s design for a new palace, after the old Palace of Westminster was largely destroyed by fire on the night of 16 October 1834.<ref name=faq /><ref name=dates>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/key-dates-/1289-90/| title=1289-1834: Big Ben and Elizabeth Tower| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> The new parliament was built in a neo-gothic style. Although Barry was the chief architect of the palace, he turned to [[Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin|Augustus Pugin]] for the design of the clock tower, which resembles earlier Pugin designs, including one for [[Scarisbrick Hall]] in Lancashire. The design for the tower was Pugin's last design before his final descent into madness and death, and Pugin himself wrote, at the time of Barry's last visit to him to collect the drawings: \"I never worked so hard in my life for Mr Barry for tomorrow I render all the designs for finishing his bell tower & it is beautiful.\"<ref name=hill>{{cite book| first=Rosemary| last=Hill| title=God's Architect: Pugin & the Building of Romantic Britain|url=https://www.amazon.com/Gods-Architect-Building-Romantic-Britain/dp/B008W30TJO#reader_B008W30TJO| publisher=Yale University Press| date=3 March 2009| page=482| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\nThe tower is designed in Pugin's celebrated [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] style, and is {{convert|315|ft|m|1}} high.<ref name=Bong>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31002198 |title=Bong! Big Ben rings in its 150th anniversary |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[NBC News]] |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=1 June 2009 }}</ref> The bottom {{convert|200|ft|m|1}} of the tower's structure consists of brickwork with sand-coloured [[Anston]] limestone [[cladding (construction)|cladding]]. The remainder of the tower's height is a framed spire of [[cast iron]]. The tower is founded on a {{convert|50|ft|m|1}} square raft, made of {{convert|10|ft|m|1}} thick concrete, at a depth of {{convert|13|ft|m|1}} below ground level. The four clock dials are {{convert|180|ft|m|1}} above ground. The interior volume of the tower is 164,200 cubic feet (4,650 cubic metres).\n\n[[File:Palace of Westminster, London - Feb 2007.jpg|thumb|The [[Palace of Westminster]], Big Ben and [[Westminster Bridge]]]]\nDespite being one of the world's most famous tourist attractions, the interior of the tower is not open to overseas visitors, though United Kingdom residents were able to arrange tours (well in advance) through their Member of Parliament before the current repair works.<ref name=tours>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/visiting/visiting-and-tours/tours-of-parliament/bigben/| title=Clock Tower tour| publisher=UK Parliament| date=21 April 2010| accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> However, the tower currently has no lift, though one is being installed, so those escorted had to climb the 334 limestone stairs to the top.<ref name=Bong />\n\nDue to changes in ground conditions since construction, the tower leans slightly to the north-west, by roughly {{convert|230|mm|in}} over 55&nbsp;m height, giving an inclination of approximately {{frac|240}}. This includes a planned maximum of 22&nbsp;mm increased tilt due to tunnelling for the [[Jubilee line]] extension.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tunnel Vision |work=Post Report Summary |publisher=Parliamentary Office of Science and Technology |date=January 1997 |url=http://www.parliament.uk/post/pn090.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121015223/http://www.parliament.uk/post/pn090.pdf |archivedate=21 November 2006 }}</ref> It leans by about  {{convert|500|mm|in}} at the finial. Experts believe the tower's lean will not be a problem for another 4,000 to 10,000 years.<ref name=\"bbcnews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-15243118| title=Clock ticking for leaning Big Ben| date=11 October 2011| work=BBC News}}</ref> Due to thermal effects it oscillates annually by a few millimetres east and west.\n\n=== Name ===\n[[File:Palace of Westminster from the dome on Methodist Central Hall.jpg|thumb|London skyline with Big Ben and environs, including the [[London Eye]], [[Portcullis House]], [[Parliament Square]], and [[St Margaret's, Westminster|St Margaret's Church]]]]\nJournalists during [[Queen Victoria]]'s reign called it ''St Stephen's Tower''. As MPs originally sat at St Stephen's Hall, these journalists referred to anything related to the House of Commons as news from \"St. Stephens\" (the Palace of Westminster contains a feature called [[St Stephen's Tower]], a smaller tower over the public entrance).<ref name=faq>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/enquiries/| title=Frequently asked questions: Big Ben and Elizabeth Tower| publisher=UK Parliament}}</ref> The usage persists in [[Welsh language|Welsh]], where the Westminster district, and Parliament by extension, is known as ''San Steffan''.\n\nOn 2 June 2012, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that 331 [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Members of Parliament]], including senior members of all three main parties, supported a proposal to change the name from ''Clock Tower'' to ''Elizabeth Tower'' in tribute to [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] in her [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|diamond jubilee year]]. This was thought to be appropriate because the large west tower now known as [[Victoria Tower]] was renamed in tribute to Queen Victoria on her diamond jubilee.<ref name=hough>{{cite news| first=Andrew| last=Hough|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9307060/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Big-Ben-to-be-renamed-Elizabeth-Tower.html| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee: 'Big Ben to be renamed Elizabeth Tower'| work=The Daily Telegraph| date=2 June 2012| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> On 26 June 2012, the House of Commons confirmed that the name change could go ahead.<ref name=\"bbc elizabeth tower\">{{cite news |first=Kayte |last=Rath |date=26 June 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18592966 |title=Big Ben's tower renamed Elizabeth Tower in honour of Queen |publisher=BBC}}</ref> The Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]], announced the change of name on 12 September 2012 at the start of [[Prime Minister's Questions]].<ref name=pmquestions>{{cite web| title=Questions to the Prime Minister|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120912/debtext/120912-0001.htm#12091223000008| work=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 12 Sept 2012| publisher=Hansard| accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref> The change was marked by a naming ceremony in which the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[John Bercow]], unveiled a name plaque attached to the tower on the adjoining Speaker's Green.<ref name=naming>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2012/september/elizabeth-tower-naming-ceremony|last=U K Parliament |title=Elizabeth Tower naming ceremony |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Clock ==\n\n=== Dials ===\n[[File:Big Ben Clock Face.jpg|thumb|One of the dials of the Great Clock of Westminster. The hour hand is {{convert|9|ft|m|1}} long and the minute hand is {{convert|14|ft|m|1}} long.]]\nThe clock and dials were designed by Augustus Pugin. Each clock dial is set in an iron frame {{convert|23|ft|m|1}} in diameter, supporting 324 pieces of opal glass, rather like a [[Stained glass|stained-glass]] window. Some of the glass pieces may be removed for inspection of the hands. The surrounds of the dials are [[Gilding|gilded]]. At the base of each clock dial in gilt letters is the [[Latin]] inscription:\n\n{{quote|<small>{{lang|la|DOMINE SALVAM FAC REGINAM NOSTRAM VICTORIAM PRIMAM}}</small>}}\n\nwhich means ''O Lord, keep safe our Queen Victoria the First''.\n\nUnlike many other [[Roman numeral]] clock dials, which show the '4' position as {{rn|IIII}}, the Great Clock faces depict '4' as {{rn|IV}}. Also, each {{rn|X}} is actually an {{rn|F}}, a Pugin feature.\n\n=== Movement ===\n[[File:Rear of Big Ben clock face.jpg|thumb|The rear of the clock face]]\nThe clock's [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]] is famous for its reliability. The designers were the lawyer and amateur [[Horology|horologist]] [[Edmund Beckett, 1st Baron Grimthorpe|Edmund Beckett Denison]], and [[George Biddell Airy|George Airy]], the [[Astronomer Royal]]. Construction was entrusted to clockmaker [[Edward John Dent]]; after his death in 1853 his stepson Frederick Dent completed the work, in 1854.<ref name=building>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/building_clock_tower/building_great_clock.cfm| title=Denison, Dent and delays| date=13 November 2009| work=Building the Great Clock| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=23 November 2009| location=London| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204153528/http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/building_clock_tower/building_great_clock.cfm| archivedate=4 December 2009| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> As the tower was not complete until 1859, Denison had time to experiment: instead of using the [[Escapement#Deadbeat escapement|deadbeat escapement]] and [[remontoire]] as originally designed, Denison invented the double three-legged [[Escapement#Gravity escapement|gravity escapement]]. This [[escapement]] provides the best separation between [[pendulum]] and clock mechanism. The pendulum is installed within an enclosed windproof box beneath the clockroom. It is {{convert|13|ft|m|1}} long, weighs {{convert|300|kg|order=flip}}, suspended on a strip of spring steel {{frac|1|64}} inch (0.40 mm) in thickness, and beats every two seconds. The clockwork mechanism in a room below weighs five tons.\n\n[[File:Winding the mechanism that powers Big Ben.webm|thumb|Winding the clock mechanism]]\nOn top of the pendulum is a small stack of old [[British one penny coin (pre-decimal)|penny coins]]; these are to adjust the time of the clock. Adding a coin has the effect of minutely lifting the position of the pendulum's [[Center of mass|centre of mass]], reducing the effective length of the pendulum rod and hence increasing the rate at which the pendulum swings. Adding or removing a penny will change the clock's speed by 0.4 seconds per day.<ref name=livingheritage>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/facts_figures/great_clock_facts.cfm |title=Great Clock facts |date=13 November 2009 |work=Big Ben |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=23 November 2009 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007101459/http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/facts_figures/great_clock_facts.cfm |archivedate=7 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The clock is hand wound (taking about 1.5 hours)<ref>{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/embed/Qad6Q_RbQQ0?rel=0| title=How Does Big Ben Keep Accurate Time?| publisher=YouTube| network=[[Science (TV network)|Science Channel]]| series=Unearthed| date=30 August 2016}}</ref> three times a week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigbenfacts.co.uk/facts/| title=BigBenFacts| website=www.bigbenfacts.co.uk| access-date=31 January 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508100757/http://www.bigbenfacts.co.uk/facts/| archive-date=8 May 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 1941, a German bombing raid damaged two of the clock's dials and sections of the tower's stepped roof and destroyed the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] chamber. Architect [[Sir Giles Gilbert Scott]] designed a new five-floor block. Two floors are occupied by the current chamber, which was used for the first time on 26 October 1950. The clock ran accurately and chimed throughout [[the Blitz]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Let's hear it again from Big Ben |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5401441/Lets-hear-it-again-from-Big-Ben.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=29 May 2009 |last=Jardine |first=Cassandra}}</ref>\n\n=== Breakdowns and other incidents ===\n==== 19th century ====\nBefore 1878: The clock stopped for the first time in its history, \"through a heavy fall of snow\" on the hands of a clock face.<ref name=\"big_ben_1878\">{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/244522110 |title=Big Ben |newspaper=The Herald (Melbourne) |issue= |location= |date=5 January 1878 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=3 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/240928160 |title=Big Ben |newspaper=The Kyneton Observer |issue= |location= |date=10 January 1878 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=2 }}</ref>\n\n21 August 1877-January 1878: The clock was stopped for three weeks to allow the tower and mechanism to be cleaned and repaired. The old escape wheel was replaced.<ref name=\"big_ben_1878\" />\n\nFebruary 1900: The heavy build-up of snow on a clock face impeded the progress of the hour hand, causing the clock to stop for about eight hours.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n==== 20th century ====\n1916: For two years during World War I, the bells were silenced and the clock faces were [[Blackout (wartime)|not illuminated]] at night to avoid guiding attacking German [[Zeppelin]]s.<ref name=Bong />\n\n29 December 1927: Snow build-up on a clock face stopped the clock.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/237529997 |title=Snow Stops Big Ben |newspaper=The Labor Daily (Sydney) |issue= |location= |date=30 December 1927 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=1 }}</ref>\n\nWinter 1928: Heavy snow stopped the clock for several hours.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n2 April 1934: The clock stopped from 7:16&nbsp;a.m. to 1:15&nbsp;pm, when it was repaired.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/128850189|title=Big Ben Stops on Holiday |newspaper=News (Adelaide) |issue= |location= |date=3 April 1934 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=10 }}</ref>\n\n23 September 1936: A painter painting the inside of the clock room placed a ladder against a shaft driving the hands, stopping the clock from 8:47 to 10&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n1 September 1939: Although the bells continued to ring, the clock faces were not illuminated at night throughout {{Nowrap|World War II}} to avoid guiding bomber pilots during the Blitz.<ref name=Bong />\n\n10 May 1941: A German bombing raid damaged two of the clock's dials.\n\n3\u20134 June 1941: The clock stopped from 10:13&nbsp;p.m. until 10:13 the following morning, after a workman repairing air-raid damage to the clock face left a hammer too close to the mechanism.<ref name=hammer>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page5437214?zoomLevel=1| work=The Morning Bulletin| location=Rockhampton| title=Big Ben stopped by hammer| date=6 June 1941| accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n25\u201326 January 1945: Extremely cold temperatures froze the rubber bushings on the quarter-bell hammers, preventing the chimes sounding from 9 p.m. on the 25th to 9 p.m. the following evening; the BBC broadcast the [[Greenwich Time Signal|pips]] in the interval.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n28 January 1947: The rubber bushings on the quarter bell hammers again froze before the clock sounded midnight, muting the chimes, though the problem was resolved by the morning.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n12 August 1949: The clock slowed by four and a half minutes after a flock of starlings perched on the minute hand.<ref name=clean>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/1501943.stm| work=BBC News| title=Big Ben's big clean| date=21 August 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n13 January 1955: The clock stopped at 3:24&nbsp;a.m. due to drifts of snow forming on the north and east dials. Small electric heaters were placed just inside these two dials which faced the full fury of the winter's blast, and this measure has helped to reduce instances of freezing in recent years.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\">{{cite book |last=MacDonald |first=Peter |title=Big Ben: The Bell, the Clock and the Tower |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aN0TDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage |date=13 October 2005 |publisher=[[The History Press]] |access-date=18 June 2017|isbn=978-0-7524-9549-1 }}</ref>\n\n18 July 1955: The rope operating the striking hammer broke, silencing the clock from 10 a.m. to 5&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\nNew Year's Eve 1962: The clock slowed due to heavy snow and ice on the hands, causing the pendulum to detach from the clockwork, as it is designed to do in such circumstances, to avoid serious damage elsewhere in the mechanism&nbsp;\u2013 the pendulum continuing to swing freely. Thus, it chimed-in the 1963 new year nine minutes late.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/nov/09/bell-tolls-for-big-ben-snow-ice-and-sunflower-effect-stop-the-clock| title=Bell tolls for Big Ben: snow, ice and sunflower effect stop the clock| first=Jeremy| last=Plester| date=9 November 2016| newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n30 January 1965: The bells were silenced during the funeral of statesman and former prime minister [[Winston Churchill]].<ref name=silenced>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-22157022| work=BBC News| title=Big Ben to be silent for Baroness Thatcher's funeral| date=15 April 2013| accessdate=7 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n9 January 1968: Snow buildup on the clock faces blocked the hands from moving, stopping the clock from 6:28 to 10:10&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n5 August 1976: First and only major breakdown. The air brake speed regulator of the chiming mechanism broke from [[torsional]] [[Fatigue (material)|fatigue]] after more than 100 years of use, causing the fully wound 4-ton weight to spin the winding drum out of the movement, causing much damage. The Great Clock was shut down for a total of 26 days over nine months&nbsp;\u2013 it was reactivated on 9 May 1977. This was the longest break in operation since its construction. During this time [[BBC Radio 4]] broadcast the pips instead.<ref name=macdonald /> Although there were minor stoppages from 1977 to 2002, when maintenance of the clock was carried out by the old firm of clockmakers [[Thwaites & Reed]], these were often repaired within the permitted two-hour downtime and not recorded as stoppages. Before 1970, maintenance was carried out by the original firm of Dents; since 2002, by parliamentary staff.\n\nMarch 1986 and January 1987: The problem of the rubber bushings on the quarter bell chimes freezing recurred, muffling the chimes.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n30 April 1997: The clock stopped 24 hours before the general election, and stopped again three weeks later.<ref name=05mystery />\n\n==== 21st century ====\n[[File:Cleaning Big Ben.jpg|thumb|upright|The south clock face being cleaned on 11 August 2007]]\n27 May 2005: The clock stopped at 10:07&nbsp;pm, possibly because of hot weather; temperatures in London had reached an unseasonable 31.8&nbsp;\u00b0C (90&nbsp;\u00b0F). It resumed, but stopped again at 10:20&nbsp;pm, and remained still for about 90 minutes before resuming.<ref name=05mystery>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4589527.stm| work=BBC News |title=Big Ben chimes stoppage mystery| date=28 May 2005| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n29 October 2005: The mechanism was stopped for about 33 hours to allow maintenance work on the clock and its chimes. It was the lengthiest maintenance shutdown in 22 years.<ref name=turnoff>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_pictures/4389002.stm| work=BBC News| title=In pictures: Big Ben's big turn off| date=29 October 2005| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n7:00&nbsp;a.m. 5 June 2006: The clock tower's \"Quarter Bells\" were taken out of commission for four weeks<ref name=hutton>{{cite news |last=Hutton |first=Robert |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000102&sid=ak.qvEQ42YM4 |title=Big Ben's Chime Won't Sound the Same to Londoners for a While |publisher=Bloomberg |date=4 June 2006 |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> as a bearing holding one of the quarter bells was worn and needed to be removed for repairs. During this period, BBC Radio 4 broadcast recordings of British [[bird song]] followed by the pips in place of the usual chimes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2006/06/bongs_and_birds.html| title=The Editors: Bongs and Birds| last=Rippon| first=Peter| date=12 June 2006| work=BBC News| access-date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n11 August 2007: Start of 6-week stoppage for maintenance. Bearings in the clock's chime train and the \"great bell\" striker were replaced, for the first time since installation.<ref name=07repair>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6941611.stm| work=BBC News| title= Big Ben silenced for repair work| date=11 August 2007| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> During the maintenance the clock was driven by an [[electric motor]].<ref name=ticking>{{cite web |url=http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART134 |title=Big Ben 1859&nbsp;\u2013 2009&nbsp;\u2013 Keeping the Great Clock ticking |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=27 May 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603211836/http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART134| archivedate=3 June 2009 | url-status=live}}</ref> Once again, BBC Radio 4 broadcast the pips during this time. The intention was that the clock should run accurately for a further 200 years before major maintenance is again required; in fact the repairs sufficed for ten years.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ed0XwaX_fHIC| last=Brand| first=Stewart| title=The Clock of the Long Now| year=2008| location=New York| isbn=978-0-7867-2292-1| publisher=Basic Books}}</ref>\n\n17 April 2013: The bells were silenced as a mark of \"profound dignity and deep respect\" during the funeral of former Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]].<ref name=watts>{{cite news| last=Watt| first=Nicholas| title=Margaret Thatcher funeral: Big Ben to be silenced as mark of respect|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/apr/15/margaret-thatcher-big-ben-silenced| accessdate=17 May 2013| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]| date=15 April 2013| location=London}}</ref>\n\nAugust 2015: The clock was discovered to be running 7 seconds fast, and coins were removed from its pendulum to correct the error, which caused it to run slow for a time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Phipps |first=Claire |title=Clockwatchers ticked off as Big Ben's chimes run seven seconds fast  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/aug/25/clockwatchers-ticked-off-as-big-bens-chimes-run-six-seconds-fast |date=25 August 2015 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n21 August 2017: Start of 4-year silencing of the chimes during maintenance and repair work to the clock mechanism, and repairs and improvements to the clock tower building. During this time, dials, hands, and lights will be removed for restoration, with at least one dial\u2014with hands driven by an electric motor\u2014left intact, functioning, and visible at any given time. Plans also include installing a lift.<ref name=BBC20170814>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40922169| work=BBC News| location=London| title=Big Ben's bongs to fall silent until 2021 for repairs| date=14 August 2017| accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> The bells, however, will still chime for events such as New Year's Eve and [[Remembrance Sunday|Remembrance Day]].<ref name=afppfp>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/big-ben-silent-bell-four-years-mps-commons-westminster-parliament-renovation-repairs-a7904056.html| title=MPs are gathering outside Big Ben to watch it bong for the final time| date=21 August 2017| newspaper=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/big-ben-will-still-bong-for-new-years-eve-and-remembrance-day-despite-four-year-silence-a3616481.html| title=Big Ben WILL still bong for New Year's Eve and Remembrance Day| newspaper=London Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\n== Bells ==\n\n=== Great Bell ===\n<!--[[Template:Bells]] and [[Big Ben bell]] redirect directly here.-->please said me me I love Shakespeare's writing not yours.\n[[File:big-ben-1858.jpg|thumb|The second \"Big Ben\" (centre) and the Quarter Bells from ''[[News of the World|The Illustrated News of the World]]'', 4 December 1858]]\n\nThe main bell,who hated you officially known as the ''Great Bell'' but better known as ''Big Ben'', is the largest bell in the tower and part of the Great Clock of Westminster.<ref name=\"greatbell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/building-clock-tower/great-bell/| title=The Great Bell \u2013 Big Ben| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> It sounds an E-natural.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ben |url=https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-information-office/Big-Ben.pdf |date=2012 |website=House of Commons |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original bell was a 16&nbsp;[[long ton|ton]] (16.3-[[tonne]]) hour bell, cast on 6 August 1856 in [[Stockton-on-Tees]] by [[John Warner & Sons]].<ref name=wbfbb /> It is thought that the bell was originally to be called ''Victoria'' or ''Royal Victoria'' in honour of Queen Victoria, but that an MP suggested the bell's current nickname of \"Big Ben\" during a Parliamentary debate; the comment is not recorded in [[Hansard]].<ref name=icons>{{cite web |url=http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/big-ben/features/how-did-big-ben-get-its-name |last=ICONS England |title=Big Ben&nbsp;\u2013 How did Big Ben get its Name? |work=Icons of England| accessdate=30 April 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124034508/http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/big-ben/features/how-did-big-ben-get-its-name |archivedate=24 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince the tower was not yet finished, the bell was mounted in [[Palace of Westminster#Grounds|New Palace Yard]] but, during testing it cracked beyond repair and a replacement had to be made. The bell was recast on 10 April 1858 at the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] as a 13{{sfrac|1|2}}&nbsp;ton (13.76-tonne) bell.<ref name=wbfbb /><ref>The actual weight quoted by the founders is 13&nbsp; [[Long ton|tons]] 10&nbsp;[[hundredweight|cwts]] 3&nbsp;[[Avoirdupois#British adaptation|qtrs]] 15&nbsp;[[Pound (mass)|lbs]].</ref> The second bell was transported from the foundry to the tower on a trolley drawn by sixteen horses, with crowds cheering its progress; it was then pulled {{convert|200|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} up to the Clock Tower's belfry, a feat that took 18 hours. It is {{convert|7|ft|6|in|m|2}} tall and {{convert|9|ft|m|2}} diameter. This new bell first chimed in July 1859; in September it too cracked under the hammer. According to the foundry's manager, George Mears, the horologist Denison had used a hammer more than twice the maximum weight specified.<ref name=wbfbb /> For three years Big Ben was taken out of commission and the hours were struck on the lowest of the quarter bells until it was repaired. To make the repair, a square piece of metal was chipped out from the rim around the crack, and the bell given an eighth of a turn so the new hammer struck in a different place.<ref name=wbfbb /> Big Ben has chimed with a slightly different tone ever since, and is still in use today with the crack unrepaired. Big Ben was the largest bell in the British Isles until \"Great Paul\", a 16{{sfrac|3|4}}&nbsp;ton (17&nbsp;tonne) bell currently hung in [[St Paul's Cathedral]], was cast in 1881.<ref name=paul>{{cite web|url=http://www.inloughborough.com/local%20history/Great_Paul.shtml| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930141731/http://www.inloughborough.com/local%20history/Great_Paul.shtml| url-status=dead| archive-date=30 September 2007| title=The History of Great Paul| publisher=Bell foundry museum, Leicester| accessdate=19 October 2008| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Chimes ===\n[[File:BBC World Service Big Ben 1-1-2009.ogg|thumb|left|A recording from the [[BBC World Service]] radio station of the [[Westminster Chimes]] and the twelve strikes of Big Ben, as broadcast at midnight, New Year's Day 2009.]]\n\nAlong with the Great Bell, the [[Belfry (architecture)|belfry]] houses four [[quarter bells]] which play the ''[[Westminster Quarters]]'' on the quarter hours. The four quarter bells sound G{{music|sharp}}, F{{music|sharp}}, E, and B. They were cast by John Warner & Sons at their Crescent Foundry in 1857 (G{{music|sharp}}, F{{music|sharp}} and B) and 1858 (E). The Foundry was in Jewin Crescent, in what is now known as [[Barbican Centre|The Barbican]], in the City of London.<ref>{{cite news| title=The New Houses of Parliament| date=16 November 1855| work=[[Evening Standard#History|The Standard]] |page=2|location=London}}</ref> The bells are sounded by hammers pulled by cables coming from the link room\u2014a low-ceiling space between the clock room and the belfry\u2014where mechanisms translate the movement of the quarter train into the sounding of the individual bells.<ref>{{cite book |last=McKay |first=Chris |title=Big Ben: the Great Clock and the Bells at the Palace of Westminster |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r5V4HUiKRCUC&pg=SA2-PA47 |date=27 May 2010 |at=2.47\u201348 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-958569-4 |access-date=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Big Ben 2001-06-27.jpg|thumb|Big Ben]]\n\nThe quarter bells play a once-repeating, 20-note sequence of rounds and four [[Change ringing|changes]] in the key of [[E major]]: 1\u20134 at quarter past, 5\u201312 at half past, 13\u201320 and 1\u20134 at quarter to, and 5\u201320 on the hour (which sounds 25 seconds before the main bell tolls the hour). Because the low bell (B) is struck twice in quick succession, there is not enough time to pull a hammer back, and it is supplied with two wrench hammers on opposite sides of the bell. The tune is that of the [[Cambridge Chimes]], first used for the chimes of [[Church of St Mary the Great, Cambridge|Great St Mary]]'s church, [[Cambridge]], and supposedly a [[Variation (music)|variation]], attributed to [[William Crotch]], based on violin [[Phrase (music)|phrases]] from the air \"[[Messiah Part III#Part III|I know that my Redeemer liveth]]\" in [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s ''[[Messiah (Handel)|Messiah]]''.<ref name=phillips>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Alan |title=The Story of Big Ben |year=1959 |publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office |page=13}}</ref><ref name=starmer>{{cite book |last=Starmer |first=William Wooding |title=Quarter Chimes and Chime Tunes |year=1910 |location=London |publisher=Novello |pages=6\u20138}}</ref> The notional words of the chime, again derived from Great St Mary's and in turn an allusion to [[Psalm 37]]:23\u201324, are: \"All through this hour/Lord be my guide/And by Thy power/No foot shall slide\". They are written on a plaque on the wall of the clock room.<ref name=milmo>{{cite news| last=Milmo| first=Cahel| title=Bong! A change of tune at Westminster| work=The Independent| date=5 June 2006|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/bong-a-change-of-tune-at-westminster-481163.html| accessdate=8 April 2008| location=London}}</ref><ref name=lockyer>{{cite book| last=Lockyer| first=Herbert| title=A Devotional Commentary on Psalms| publisher=Kregel Christian Books| date=1 January 1993| location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=08MSVzXA_Z8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=A+devotional+commentary+on+psalms#v=onepage&q=westminster| isbn=978-0-8254-9742-1| page=149}}</ref>\n\nOne of the requirements for the clock was that the first stroke of the hour bell should be correct to within one second per day. The tolerance is with reference to [[Greenwich Mean Time]] ([[British Summer Time|BST]] in summer).<ref name=Bong /><ref>Steve Jaggs, Keeper of the Clock, interviewed on ''Sky News'', 26 April 2016.</ref><ref name=whitechapel>{{cite web| publisher=Whitechapel Bell Foundry| title=The Story of Big Ben|url=http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/bigben.htm| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> So, at twelve o'clock, for example, it is the first of the twelve hour-bell strikes that signifies the hour (the New Year on New Year's Eve at midnight). The time signalled by the last of the \"six pips\" ([[UTC]]) may be fractionally different.\n\n== Nickname ==\nThe origin of the nickname ''Big Ben'' is the subject of some debate. The nickname was applied first to the Great Bell; it may have been named after [[Benjamin Hall, 1st Baron Llanover|Sir Benjamin Hall]], who oversaw the installation of the Great Bell, or after English heavyweight boxing champion [[Benjamin Caunt]].<ref name=wbfbb /><ref name=\"greatbell\" /><ref name=\"UKparlBB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/building-clock-tower/great-bell/| title=The Great Bell&nbsp;\u2013 Big Ben| date=13 November 2009| work=Living Heritage| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Now ''Big Ben'' is often used, by extension, to refer to the clock, the tower and the bell collectively, although the nickname is not universally accepted as referring to the clock and tower.<ref name=BigBenCOD /><ref name=Britannica>{{cite web| title=Big Ben|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/64921/Big-Ben| publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online| accessdate=27 October 2008| first=Jonathan D.| last=Betts| date=26 November 2008| work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081102173629/http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/64921/Big-Ben| archivedate=2 November 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=Columbia>{{cite web| title=Big Ben|url=http://www.bartleby.com/65/bi/BigBen.html| publisher=Columbia University Press| accessdate=27 October 2008| date=July 2001| work=The Columbia Encyclopedia| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010153226/http://www.bartleby.com/65/bi/BigBen.html| archivedate=10 October 2008| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Encarta>{{cite web |title=Big Ben |url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/dictionary_1861813060/Big_Ben.html |publisher=Microsoft Corporation |accessdate=14 January 2009 |year=2009 |work=Encarta World English Dictionary [North American Edition] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kwQ5lg9Y?url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/dictionary_1861813060/Big_Ben.html |archivedate=31 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Some authors of works about the tower, clock and bell sidestep the issue by using the words ''Big Ben'' first in the title, then going on to clarify that the subject of the book is the clock and tower as well as the bell.<ref name=macdonald>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_FuPAwAAQBAJ| last=Macdonald| first=Peter G| title=Big Ben: The Bell, The Clock And The Tower| date=25 January 2005| location=Stroud, Gloucestershire| isbn=978-0-7524-9549-1}}</ref><ref name=Lockhart>{{cite book| last=Lockhart| first=Ann| title=Big Ben and the Westminster Clock Tower| date=1997| location=Stroud, Gloucestershire| isbn=978-0-85372-839-9}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, [[Satire|satirical]] news site [[The Rochdale Herald]] published a spoof article stating that the bell was to be renamed \"Massive Mohammed\". Many people mistook this for a genuine news story and were widely ridiculed on [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/17/people-actually-believed-that-big-ben-was-going-to-be-renamed-massive-mohammed-6859959/| title=People actually believed that Big Ben was going to be renamed 'Massive Mohammed'| first=Ashitha| last=Nagesh| date=17 August 2017| newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]| location=London| access-date=23 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/stephaniemcneal/massive-mohammed| title=This Fake Story Claiming Big Ben Will Be Renamed For Muslims Is Making A Lot of People Mad| work=[[BuzzFeed]]| access-date=23 August 2017| language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/big-ben-renamed-massive-mohammed-fake-news-parody-article-spoof-site-7900861| title=Someone joked that Big Ben would be renamed Massive Mohammed and people were furious| date=18 August 2017| work=[[Indy100]]| access-date=23 August 2017| language=en-GB}}</ref> This even inspired the creation of two online [[petition]]s.\n\n== Cultural significance ==\n[[File:Whitehall Street Traffic.jpg|thumb|[[Double-decker bus]]es frame a busy [[Whitehall]] with Big Ben in the background.]]\n\nThe clock has become a [[Culture of the United Kingdom|cultural symbol of the United Kingdom]], particularly in the visual media. When a television or film-maker wishes to indicate a generic location in the country, a popular way to do so is to show an image of the tower, often with a [[AEC Routemaster|red double-decker bus]] or [[black cab]] in the foreground.<ref name=patterson>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=John |title=City Light |url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/filmandmusic/story/0,,2091939,00.html |date=1 June 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618191946/http://arts.guardian.co.uk/filmandmusic/story/0%2C%2C2091939%2C00.html |archive-date=18 June 2008 |location=London |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=26 December 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a survey of 2,000 people found that the tower was the most popular landmark in the United Kingdom.<ref name=landmark>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/7337319.stm| work=BBC News| title=Big Ben 'UK's favourite landmark'| date=9 April 2008| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> It has also been named as the most iconic [[London in film|film location in London]].<ref name=iconic>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/2007/10/21/big-ben-most-iconic-london-film-location-385597| newspaper=Metro| title=Big Ben most iconic London film location| date=21 October 2007| location=London| accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Big Ben illuminated.jpg|thumb|left|Big Ben's dials and belfry are illuminated at night.]]\n\nThe sound of the clock chiming has also been used this way in audio media, but as the Westminster Quarters are heard from other clocks and other devices, the sound is by no means unique. Big Ben is a focal point of [[New Year's Eve#England|New Year celebrations in the United Kingdom]], with radio and television stations airing its chimes to welcome the start of the New Year. To welcome in 2012, the clock tower was lit with fireworks that exploded at every toll of Big Ben.<ref name=welcome2012>{{cite web| title=Fireworks going off at the London Eye and Big Ben to welcome 2012 in London|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q1yLRK2M8YQ |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> Similarly, on [[Remembrance Day]], the chimes of Big Ben are broadcast to mark the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month and the start of the two minutes' silence.<ref name=remembrance>{{cite news |title=Remembrance Day across the UK |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4010971.stm |work=BBC News |date=14 November 2004 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> The chimes of Big Ben have also been used at the state funerals of monarchs on three occasions: firstly, at the [[funeral of King Edward VII]] in 1910, when Big Ben chimed 68 times, one stroke for each year of the monarch's life; secondly, at the funeral of King George V in 1936 (70 strokes); and finally, at the funeral of King George VI in 1952 (56 strokes).<ref>{{cite book|authors=[[Ben Weinreb|Weinreb, Ben]] and [[Christopher Hibbert|Hibbert, Christopher]]|title=The London Encyclopaedia|edition=reprint|page=66|year=1992|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|title-link=The London Encyclopaedia}}</ref>\n\nLondoners who live an appropriate distance from the tower and Big Ben can, by means of listening to the chimes both live and on analogue radio, hear the bell strike thirteen times. This is possible because the electronically transmitted chimes arrive virtually instantaneously, while the \"live\" sound is delayed travelling through the air since the [[speed of sound]] is relatively slow.<ref name=strike13>{{cite news |title=How to make Big Ben's clock strike 13 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11684375 |work=BBC News |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[ITN]]'s ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' opening sequence formerly featured an image of the tower with the sound of Big Ben's chimes punctuating the announcement of the news headlines of the day.<ref name=robinson>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/oct/22/itv-news-at-ten-big-ben| newspaper=The Guardian| title=ITV to drop Big Ben from News at Ten titles| first=James| last=Robinson| date=22 October 2009| accessdate=13 August 2012| location=London}}</ref> The Big Ben chimes (known within ITN as \"The Bongs\") continue to be used during the headlines and all [[ITV News]] bulletins use a graphic based on the Westminster clock dial. Big Ben can also be heard striking the hour before some news bulletins on BBC Radio 4 (6 p.m. and midnight, plus 10&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays) and the BBC World Service, a practice that began on 31 December 1923. The sound of the chimes is sent live from a microphone permanently installed in the tower and connected by line to [[Broadcasting House]].<ref name=\"microphone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/0plchBL6QIaFgEmPi5PzdA |title=Big Ben Microphone |publisher=BBC |access-date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the close of the polls for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] the results of the national exit poll were projected onto the south side of the tower.<ref name=2010election>{{cite web| title=General election results beamed onto Big Ben |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2010/05/big-ben-projections/ |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=30 April 2016| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111152210/http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2010/05/big-ben-projections/| archivedate= 11 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On 27 July 2012, starting at 8:12 a.m, Big Ben chimed 30 times, to welcome the [[2012 Summer Olympics|Games of the 30th Olympiad]], which officially began that day, to London.<ref>{{cite web| title=Big Ben rings in Olympic Morning| work=[[ITV News]]| publisher=YouTube| date=27 July 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4TKKZsMl9Dg | accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== 2017 renovation ==\n[[File:Big Ben Covered in Scaffolding.jpg|thumb|Scaffolding was put up in 2017.]]\n\nOn 21 August 2017, Big Ben's chimes were silenced for four years to allow essential restoration work to be carried out on the tower. The decision to silence the bells was made to protect the hearing of the workers on the tower, and drew much criticism from senior [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] and the then Prime Minister [[Theresa May]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/16/theresa-may-says-cant-right-big-ben-besilent-four-years/|title=Theresa May says 'it can't be right for Big Ben to be silent for four years'|last=Hughes|first=Laura|date=2017-08-16|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The striking and tolling of the bells for important occasions, such as New Year's Eve and Remembrance Sunday, will be handled via an electric motor; and at least one of the four clock faces will remain visible during the restoration. Scaffolding was put up around the tower immediately after the bells were silenced. The original cost of the project to the taxpayers and creditors was estimated to be roughly \u00a329 million, but this was then more than doubled, to \u00a369 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41444415|title=Big Ben tower repair costs double|date=2017-09-29|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> In February 2020 it was confirmed that the renovations had revealed that the Elizabeth Tower had sustained greater damage than originally thought in the May 1941 bombing raid that destroyed the adjacent House of Commons. Other costly discoveries included [[asbestos]] in the belfry, the \"extensive\" use of lead paint, broken glass on the clock dials, and serious deterioration to the tower's intricate stone carvings due to air pollution.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite article| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/13/asbestos-and-damage-discovery-inflates-big-ben-repair-bill-to-80m| title=Wartime bomb damage and asbestos inflates Big Ben repair bill to \u20a480m| author=Rajeev Syal| publisher=The Guardian| date=2020-02-13| access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> The cost of addressing the new problems was estimated at \u20a418.6 million, bringing the total budget for restoring the Elizabeth Tower to nearly \u20a480 million.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The additional renovation work was not set to derail the completion of the project: Big Ben will resume its usual striking and tolling in 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40922169|title=Big Ben's bongs to fall silent until 2021|date=2017-08-14|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe aim of the renovation is to repair and conserve the tower, upgrading facilities as necessary, and ensuring the tower's integrity for future generations. The last significant renovation work to the tower was carried out in 1983\u201385. The {{convert|96|m|adj=on}} high structure is exposed to the elements, resulting in cracks and other damage to the masonry and rust damage to the ironwork. The 2,567 cast-iron roof tiles will be removed and replaced, and a lift will be installed to make access easier, along with a basic washroom with running water. The Ayrton Light at the top of the tower, which is lit when Parliament is sitting, will also be fully dismantled and restored with the other lights in the Belfry, the lights being replaced with low energy [[Light-emitting diode|LEDs]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36138203|title=Big Ben to be silenced for \u00a329m refit|date=2016-04-26|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> One of the most visible changes to the tower will be the restoration of the clock-face framework to its original colour of [[Prussian blue]], used when the tower was first built in 1859, with the black paint used to cover up the soot-stained dial frames being stripped away. The clock faces are also to be regilded, and the shields of St George are to be repainted in their original red and white colours. The 1,296 pieces of glass that make up the clock faces are also to be removed and replaced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/news/big-ben-goes-blue|title=Big Ben Has Been Repainted Blue|date=2019-03-21|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/elizabeth-tower-and-big-ben-conservation-works-2017-/elizabeth-tower-conservation-contract-awarded/|title=Elizabeth Tower contract awarded \u2013 News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|London}}\n* [[Big Ben Aden]]\n* [[Little Ben]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|1=\"Big Ben\"|display=Big Ben|d=Q37733713|voy=Westminster|n=no|b=no|v=no|q=no}}\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/bigben Official website of Big Ben] at UK Parliament\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/ The Palace of Westminster] at UK Parliament\n* [http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/bigben.htm Big Ben] at Whitechapel Bell Foundry\n* [http://www.houghtonlespring.org.uk/articles/big_ben_clapper.htm Big Ben's Clapper] at Houghton-le-Spring Heritage Society\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/uk_parliament/tags/bigben Interior photos of  the tower] at UK Parliament's [[Flickr]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071012110834/http://www.raeng.org.uk/news/publications/list/lectures/Two_Towers_Lecture.pdf \"A tale of Two Towers: Big Ben and Pisa\"]\u2014transcript of a lecture by Prof. [[John Burland]]\n\n=== Videos ===\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Elffjsjbio ''The Mechanical Genius of Big Ben'' (2017)] documentary by [[Discovery (UK and Ireland)|Discovery]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZukDFfy5cnc ''Big Ben's a Hundred'' (1959)] newsreel by [[British Path\u00e9]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XtV-G2P0A74 ''Big Ben's Clean Up'' (1955)] by British Path\u00e9\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y88TCW11SHM ''Big Ben'' (1948)] by British Path\u00e9\n\n{{Bells}}\n{{London landmarks}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Bell towers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Clock towers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in London]]\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1859]]\n[[Category:Inclined towers]]\n[[Category:Individual clocks in England]]\n[[Category:National government buildings in London]]\n[[Category:Palace of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 1859]]\n[[Category:Towers in London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the City of Westminster]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Bell within the clock tower at the Palace of Westminster in London, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Elizabeth Tower\n| native_name         = \n| alternate_names     = Big Ben\n| image               = Clock Tower - Palace of Westminster, London - May 2007.jpg\n| caption             = \n| building_type       = [[Clock tower]]\n| architectural_style = [[Gothic Revival]]\n| structural_system   = \n| location            = [[Westminster]], London, England\n| owner               = \n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|51.5007|-0.1245|display=inline,title|region:GB_type:landmark}}\n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = {{start date and age|df=yes|31 May 1859}}\n| height              = {{convert|96|m|ft}}\n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 11\n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = [[Augustus Pugin]]\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n}}\n'''Big Ben''' is the nickname for the Great Bell of the [[striking clock]] at the north end of the [[Palace of Westminster]] in London<ref name=wbfbb>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/bigben.htm| title=The Story of Big Ben|publisher=Whitechapel Bell Foundry| accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> and is usually [[Metonymy|extended to refer]] to both the clock and the [[clock tower]].<ref name=BigBenCOD>{{cite book| last=Fowler| first=H. W.| authorlink=Henry Watson Fowler| others=First edited by H. W. Fowler and F. G. Fowler| title=The Concise Oxford dictionary of current English| edition=Sixth| year=1976| page=[https://archive.org/details/conciseoxforddic00syke/page/95 95]| publisher=[[Clarendon Press]]| isbn=978-0-19-861121-9| quote=Big Ben, great bell, clock, and tower, of Houses of Parliament| url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/conciseoxforddic00syke/page/95}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_2016_04_26\">{{cite web| title=Big Ben 'bongs' to be silenced for \u00a329m refurbishment|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36138203| work=BBC News| publisher=BBC| accessdate=26 April 2016| date=26 April 2016}}</ref> The official name of the tower in which Big Ben is located was originally the '''Clock Tower''', but it was renamed '''Elizabeth Tower''' in 2012 to mark the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]].\n\nThe tower was designed by [[Augustus Pugin]] in a [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-Gothic style]]. When completed in 1859, its clock was the largest and most accurate four-faced striking and chiming clock in the world.<ref>{{cite news| title=Why is Big Ben falling silent?|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20160704-the-big-ben-renovation-and-how-the-clock-works| last=Excell| first=Jon| publisher=BBC| date=5 July 2016}}</ref> The tower stands {{convert|315|ft|m|0}} tall, and the climb from ground level to the belfry is 334 steps. Its base is square, measuring {{convert|39|ft|m|0}} on each side. Dials of the clock are {{convert|23|ft|m|1}} in diameter. On 31 May 2009, celebrations were held to mark the tower's 150th anniversary.<ref name=\"parliament.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART16| title=Join in the anniversary celebrations| publisher=UK Parliament| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202121929/http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART16| archivedate=2 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBig Ben is the largest of the tower's five bells and weighs {{convert|13.5|LT|t ST|1|abbr=off|lk=on}}.<ref name=wbfbb /> It was the largest bell in the United Kingdom for 23 years. The origin of the bell's nickname is open to question; it may be named after Sir [[Benjamin Hall, 1st Baron Llanover|Benjamin Hall]], who oversaw its installation, or [[heavyweight]] [[boxing]] champion [[Benjamin Caunt]]. Four [[quarter bells]] chime at 15, 30 and 45 minutes past the hour and just before Big Ben tolls on the hour. The clock uses its original Victorian mechanism, but an electric motor can be used as a backup.\n\nThe tower is a [[Culture of the United Kingdom|British cultural icon]] recognised all over the world. It is one of the most prominent symbols of the United Kingdom and parliamentary democracy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/426|title=Palace of Westminster and Westminster Abbey including Saint Margaret's Church| publisher=[[UNESCO]]}}</ref> and it is often used in the [[establishing shot]] of films set in London.<ref>{{cite news| title=Big Ben in films and popular culture|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/10525651/Big-Ben-in-films-and-popular-culture.html| newspaper=The Daily Telegraph| date=8 November 2016}}</ref> The clock tower has been part of a [[Grade I listed building]] since 1970 and a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] since 1987.\n\nOn 21 August 2017, a four-year schedule of renovation works began on the tower, which are to include the addition of a [[elevator|lift]]. There are also plans to re-glaze and repaint the clock dials. With a few exceptions, such as New Year's Eve and [[Remembrance Sunday]], the bells are to be silent until the work is completed in 2021.\n\n== Tower ==\n=== Origin ===\n[[File:Gary O'Donoghue on the Elizabeth Tower.ogg|thumb|Audio description of the tower by [[Gary O'Donoghue]]]]\nElizabeth Tower, previously called the Clock Tower<!--Not St Stephen's -- see [[Talk:Big Ben/Archive 2#St Stephen's Tower]]--> but more popularly known as Big Ben,<ref name=BBC_2016_04_26 /><ref name=\"parliament.uk\" /> was raised as a part of [[Charles Barry]]'s design for a new palace, after the old Palace of Westminster was largely destroyed by fire on the night of 16 October 1834.<ref name=faq /><ref name=dates>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/key-dates-/1289-90/| title=1289-1834: Big Ben and Elizabeth Tower| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> The new parliament was built in a neo-gothic style. Although Barry was the chief architect of the palace, he turned to [[Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin|Augustus Pugin]] for the design of the clock tower, which resembles earlier Pugin designs, including one for [[Scarisbrick Hall]] in Lancashire. The design for the tower was Pugin's last design before his final descent into madness and death, and Pugin himself wrote, at the time of Barry's last visit to him to collect the drawings: \"I never worked so hard in my life for Mr Barry for tomorrow I render all the designs for finishing his bell tower & it is beautiful.\"<ref name=hill>{{cite book| first=Rosemary| last=Hill| title=God's Architect: Pugin & the Building of Romantic Britain|url=https://www.amazon.com/Gods-Architect-Building-Romantic-Britain/dp/B008W30TJO#reader_B008W30TJO| publisher=Yale University Press| date=3 March 2009| page=482| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\nThe tower is designed in Pugin's celebrated [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] style, and is {{convert|315|ft|m|1}} high.<ref name=Bong>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31002198 |title=Bong! Big Ben rings in its 150th anniversary |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[NBC News]] |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=1 June 2009 }}</ref> The bottom {{convert|200|ft|m|1}} of the tower's structure consists of brickwork with sand-coloured [[Anston]] limestone [[cladding (construction)|cladding]]. The remainder of the tower's height is a framed spire of [[cast iron]]. The tower is founded on a {{convert|50|ft|m|1}} square raft, made of {{convert|10|ft|m|1}} thick concrete, at a depth of {{convert|13|ft|m|1}} below ground level. The four clock dials are {{convert|180|ft|m|1}} above ground. The interior volume of the tower is 164,200 cubic feet (4,650 cubic metres).\n\n[[File:Palace of Westminster, London - Feb 2007.jpg|thumb|The [[Palace of Westminster]], Big Ben and [[Westminster Bridge]]]]\nDespite being one of the world's most famous tourist attractions, the interior of the tower is not open to overseas visitors, though United Kingdom residents were able to arrange tours (well in advance) through their Member of Parliament before the current repair works.<ref name=tours>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/visiting/visiting-and-tours/tours-of-parliament/bigben/| title=Clock Tower tour| publisher=UK Parliament| date=21 April 2010| accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> However, the tower currently has no lift, though one is being installed, so those escorted had to climb the 334 limestone stairs to the top.<ref name=Bong />\n\nDue to changes in ground conditions since construction, the tower leans slightly to the north-west, by roughly {{convert|230|mm|in}} over 55&nbsp;m height, giving an inclination of approximately {{frac|240}}. This includes a planned maximum of 22&nbsp;mm increased tilt due to tunnelling for the [[Jubilee line]] extension.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tunnel Vision |work=Post Report Summary |publisher=Parliamentary Office of Science and Technology |date=January 1997 |url=http://www.parliament.uk/post/pn090.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121015223/http://www.parliament.uk/post/pn090.pdf |archivedate=21 November 2006 }}</ref> It leans by about  {{convert|500|mm|in}} at the finial. Experts believe the tower's lean will not be a problem for another 4,000 to 10,000 years.<ref name=\"bbcnews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-15243118| title=Clock ticking for leaning Big Ben| date=11 October 2011| work=BBC News}}</ref> Due to thermal effects it oscillates annually by a few millimetres east and west.\n\n=== Name ===\n[[File:Palace of Westminster from the dome on Methodist Central Hall.jpg|thumb|London skyline with Big Ben and environs, including the [[London Eye]], [[Portcullis House]], [[Parliament Square]], and [[St Margaret's, Westminster|St Margaret's Church]]]]\nJournalists during [[Queen Victoria]]'s reign called it ''St Stephen's Tower''. As MPs originally sat at St Stephen's Hall, these journalists referred to anything related to the House of Commons as news from \"St. Stephens\" (the Palace of Westminster contains a feature called [[St Stephen's Tower]], a smaller tower over the public entrance).<ref name=faq>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/enquiries/| title=Frequently asked questions: Big Ben and Elizabeth Tower| publisher=UK Parliament}}</ref> The usage persists in [[Welsh language|Welsh]], where the Westminster district, and Parliament by extension, is known as ''San Steffan''.\n\nOn 2 June 2012, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that 331 [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Members of Parliament]], including senior members of all three main parties, supported a proposal to change the name from ''Clock Tower'' to ''Elizabeth Tower'' in tribute to [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] in her [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|diamond jubilee year]]. This was thought to be appropriate because the large west tower now known as [[Victoria Tower]] was renamed in tribute to Queen Victoria on her diamond jubilee.<ref name=hough>{{cite news| first=Andrew| last=Hough|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/the_queens_diamond_jubilee/9307060/The-Queens-Diamond-Jubilee-Big-Ben-to-be-renamed-Elizabeth-Tower.html| title=The Queen's Diamond Jubilee: 'Big Ben to be renamed Elizabeth Tower'| work=The Daily Telegraph| date=2 June 2012| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> On 26 June 2012, the House of Commons confirmed that the name change could go ahead.<ref name=\"bbc elizabeth tower\">{{cite news |first=Kayte |last=Rath |date=26 June 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18592966 |title=Big Ben's tower renamed Elizabeth Tower in honour of Queen |publisher=BBC}}</ref> The Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]], announced the change of name on 12 September 2012 at the start of [[Prime Minister's Questions]].<ref name=pmquestions>{{cite web| title=Questions to the Prime Minister|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120912/debtext/120912-0001.htm#12091223000008| work=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 12 Sept 2012| publisher=Hansard| accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref> The change was marked by a naming ceremony in which the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[John Bercow]], unveiled a name plaque attached to the tower on the adjoining Speaker's Green.<ref name=naming>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2012/september/elizabeth-tower-naming-ceremony|last=U K Parliament |title=Elizabeth Tower naming ceremony |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Clock ==\n\n=== Dials ===\n[[File:Big Ben Clock Face.jpg|thumb|One of the dials of the Great Clock of Westminster. The hour hand is {{convert|9|ft|m|1}} long and the minute hand is {{convert|14|ft|m|1}} long.]]\nThe clock and dials were designed by Augustus Pugin. Each clock dial is set in an iron frame {{convert|23|ft|m|1}} in diameter, supporting 324 pieces of opal glass, rather like a [[Stained glass|stained-glass]] window. Some of the glass pieces may be removed for inspection of the hands. The surrounds of the dials are [[Gilding|gilded]]. At the base of each clock dial in gilt letters is the [[Latin]] inscription:\n\n{{quote|<small>{{lang|la|DOMINE SALVAM FAC REGINAM NOSTRAM VICTORIAM PRIMAM}}</small>}}\n\nwhich means ''O Lord, keep safe our Queen Victoria the First''.\n\nUnlike many other [[Roman numeral]] clock dials, which show the '4' position as {{rn|IIII}}, the Great Clock faces depict '4' as {{rn|IV}}. Also, each {{rn|X}} is actually an {{rn|F}}, a Pugin feature.\n\n=== Movement ===\n[[File:Rear of Big Ben clock face.jpg|thumb|The rear of the clock face]]\nThe clock's [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]] is famous for its reliability. The designers were the lawyer and amateur [[Horology|horologist]] [[Edmund Beckett, 1st Baron Grimthorpe|Edmund Beckett Denison]], and [[George Biddell Airy|George Airy]], the [[Astronomer Royal]]. Construction was entrusted to clockmaker [[Edward John Dent]]; after his death in 1853 his stepson Frederick Dent completed the work, in 1854.<ref name=building>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/building_clock_tower/building_great_clock.cfm| title=Denison, Dent and delays| date=13 November 2009| work=Building the Great Clock| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=23 November 2009| location=London| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204153528/http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/building_clock_tower/building_great_clock.cfm| archivedate=4 December 2009| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref> As the tower was not complete until 1859, Denison had time to experiment: instead of using the [[Escapement#Deadbeat escapement|deadbeat escapement]] and [[remontoire]] as originally designed, Denison invented the double three-legged [[Escapement#Gravity escapement|gravity escapement]]. This [[escapement]] provides the best separation between [[pendulum]] and clock mechanism. The pendulum is installed within an enclosed windproof box beneath the clockroom. It is {{convert|13|ft|m|1}} long, weighs {{convert|300|kg|order=flip}}, suspended on a strip of spring steel {{frac|1|64}} inch (0.40 mm) in thickness, and beats every two seconds. The clockwork mechanism in a room below weighs five tons.\n\n[[File:Winding the mechanism that powers Big Ben.webm|thumb|Winding the clock mechanism]]\nOn top of the pendulum is a small stack of old [[British one penny coin (pre-decimal)|penny coins]]; these are to adjust the time of the clock. Adding a coin has the effect of minutely lifting the position of the pendulum's [[Center of mass|centre of mass]], reducing the effective length of the pendulum rod and hence increasing the rate at which the pendulum swings. Adding or removing a penny will change the clock's speed by 0.4 seconds per day.<ref name=livingheritage>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/facts_figures/great_clock_facts.cfm |title=Great Clock facts |date=13 November 2009 |work=Big Ben |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=23 November 2009 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007101459/http://www.parliament.uk/about/livingheritage/building/big_ben/facts_figures/great_clock_facts.cfm |archivedate=7 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The clock is hand wound (taking about 1.5 hours)<ref>{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/embed/Qad6Q_RbQQ0?rel=0| title=How Does Big Ben Keep Accurate Time?| publisher=YouTube| network=[[Science (TV network)|Science Channel]]| series=Unearthed| date=30 August 2016}}</ref> three times a week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigbenfacts.co.uk/facts/| title=BigBenFacts| website=www.bigbenfacts.co.uk| access-date=31 January 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508100757/http://www.bigbenfacts.co.uk/facts/| archive-date=8 May 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 1941, a German bombing raid damaged two of the clock's dials and sections of the tower's stepped roof and destroyed the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] chamber. Architect [[Sir Giles Gilbert Scott]] designed a new five-floor block. Two floors are occupied by the current chamber, which was used for the first time on 26 October 1950. The clock ran accurately and chimed throughout [[the Blitz]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Let's hear it again from Big Ben |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5401441/Lets-hear-it-again-from-Big-Ben.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=29 May 2009 |last=Jardine |first=Cassandra}}</ref>\n\n=== Breakdowns and other incidents ===\n==== 19th century ====\nBefore 1878: The clock stopped for the first time in its history, \"through a heavy fall of snow\" on the hands of a clock face.<ref name=\"big_ben_1878\">{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/244522110 |title=Big Ben |newspaper=The Herald (Melbourne) |issue= |location= |date=5 January 1878 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=3 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/240928160 |title=Big Ben |newspaper=The Kyneton Observer |issue= |location= |date=10 January 1878 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=2 }}</ref>\n\n21 August 1877-January 1878: The clock was stopped for three weeks to allow the tower and mechanism to be cleaned and repaired. The old escape wheel was replaced.<ref name=\"big_ben_1878\" />\n\nFebruary 1900: The heavy build-up of snow on a clock face impeded the progress of the hour hand, causing the clock to stop for about eight hours.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n==== 20th century ====\n1916: For two years during World War I, the bells were silenced and the clock faces were [[Blackout (wartime)|not illuminated]] at night to avoid guiding attacking German [[Zeppelin]]s.<ref name=Bong />\n\n29 December 1927: Snow build-up on a clock face stopped the clock.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/237529997 |title=Snow Stops Big Ben |newspaper=The Labor Daily (Sydney) |issue= |location= |date=30 December 1927 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=1 }}</ref>\n\nWinter 1928: Heavy snow stopped the clock for several hours.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n2 April 1934: The clock stopped from 7:16&nbsp;a.m. to 1:15&nbsp;pm, when it was repaired.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/128850189|title=Big Ben Stops on Holiday |newspaper=News (Adelaide) |issue= |location= |date=3 April 1934 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |page=10 }}</ref>\n\n23 September 1936: A painter painting the inside of the clock room placed a ladder against a shaft driving the hands, stopping the clock from 8:47 to 10&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n1 September 1939: Although the bells continued to ring, the clock faces were not illuminated at night throughout {{Nowrap|World War II}} to avoid guiding bomber pilots during the Blitz.<ref name=Bong />\n\n10 May 1941: A German bombing raid damaged two of the clock's dials.\n\n3\u20134 June 1941: The clock stopped from 10:13&nbsp;p.m. until 10:13 the following morning, after a workman repairing air-raid damage to the clock face left a hammer too close to the mechanism.<ref name=hammer>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page5437214?zoomLevel=1| work=The Morning Bulletin| location=Rockhampton| title=Big Ben stopped by hammer| date=6 June 1941| accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n25\u201326 January 1945: Extremely cold temperatures froze the rubber bushings on the quarter-bell hammers, preventing the chimes sounding from 9 p.m. on the 25th to 9 p.m. the following evening; the BBC broadcast the [[Greenwich Time Signal|pips]] in the interval.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n28 January 1947: The rubber bushings on the quarter bell hammers again froze before the clock sounded midnight, muting the chimes, though the problem was resolved by the morning.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n12 August 1949: The clock slowed by four and a half minutes after a flock of starlings perched on the minute hand.<ref name=clean>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/1501943.stm| work=BBC News| title=Big Ben's big clean| date=21 August 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n13 January 1955: The clock stopped at 3:24&nbsp;a.m. due to drifts of snow forming on the north and east dials. Small electric heaters were placed just inside these two dials which faced the full fury of the winter's blast, and this measure has helped to reduce instances of freezing in recent years.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\">{{cite book |last=MacDonald |first=Peter |title=Big Ben: The Bell, the Clock and the Tower |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aN0TDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage |date=13 October 2005 |publisher=[[The History Press]] |access-date=18 June 2017|isbn=978-0-7524-9549-1 }}</ref>\n\n18 July 1955: The rope operating the striking hammer broke, silencing the clock from 10 a.m. to 5&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\nNew Year's Eve 1962: The clock slowed due to heavy snow and ice on the hands, causing the pendulum to detach from the clockwork, as it is designed to do in such circumstances, to avoid serious damage elsewhere in the mechanism&nbsp;\u2013 the pendulum continuing to swing freely. Thus, it chimed-in the 1963 new year nine minutes late.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/nov/09/bell-tolls-for-big-ben-snow-ice-and-sunflower-effect-stop-the-clock| title=Bell tolls for Big Ben: snow, ice and sunflower effect stop the clock| first=Jeremy| last=Plester| date=9 November 2016| newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n30 January 1965: The bells were silenced during the funeral of statesman and former prime minister [[Winston Churchill]].<ref name=silenced>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-22157022| work=BBC News| title=Big Ben to be silent for Baroness Thatcher's funeral| date=15 April 2013| accessdate=7 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n9 January 1968: Snow buildup on the clock faces blocked the hands from moving, stopping the clock from 6:28 to 10:10&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n5 August 1976: First and only major breakdown. The air brake speed regulator of the chiming mechanism broke from [[torsional]] [[Fatigue (material)|fatigue]] after more than 100 years of use, causing the fully wound 4-ton weight to spin the winding drum out of the movement, causing much damage. The Great Clock was shut down for a total of 26 days over nine months&nbsp;\u2013 it was reactivated on 9 May 1977. This was the longest break in operation since its construction. During this time [[BBC Radio 4]] broadcast the pips instead.<ref name=macdonald /> Although there were minor stoppages from 1977 to 2002, when maintenance of the clock was carried out by the old firm of clockmakers [[Thwaites & Reed]], these were often repaired within the permitted two-hour downtime and not recorded as stoppages. Before 1970, maintenance was carried out by the original firm of Dents; since 2002, by parliamentary staff.\n\nMarch 1986 and January 1987: The problem of the rubber bushings on the quarter bell chimes freezing recurred, muffling the chimes.<ref name=\"Big_Ben_Clock\" />\n\n30 April 1997: The clock stopped 24 hours before the general election, and stopped again three weeks later.<ref name=05mystery />\n\n==== 21st century ====\n[[File:Cleaning Big Ben.jpg|thumb|upright|The south clock face being cleaned on 11 August 2007]]\n27 May 2005: The clock stopped at 10:07&nbsp;pm, possibly because of hot weather; temperatures in London had reached an unseasonable 31.8&nbsp;\u00b0C (90&nbsp;\u00b0F). It resumed, but stopped again at 10:20&nbsp;pm, and remained still for about 90 minutes before resuming.<ref name=05mystery>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4589527.stm| work=BBC News |title=Big Ben chimes stoppage mystery| date=28 May 2005| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n29 October 2005: The mechanism was stopped for about 33 hours to allow maintenance work on the clock and its chimes. It was the lengthiest maintenance shutdown in 22 years.<ref name=turnoff>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_pictures/4389002.stm| work=BBC News| title=In pictures: Big Ben's big turn off| date=29 October 2005| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n7:00&nbsp;a.m. 5 June 2006: The clock tower's \"Quarter Bells\" were taken out of commission for four weeks<ref name=hutton>{{cite news |last=Hutton |first=Robert |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000102&sid=ak.qvEQ42YM4 |title=Big Ben's Chime Won't Sound the Same to Londoners for a While |publisher=Bloomberg |date=4 June 2006 |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> as a bearing holding one of the quarter bells was worn and needed to be removed for repairs. During this period, BBC Radio 4 broadcast recordings of British [[bird song]] followed by the pips in place of the usual chimes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2006/06/bongs_and_birds.html| title=The Editors: Bongs and Birds| last=Rippon| first=Peter| date=12 June 2006| work=BBC News| access-date=10 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n11 August 2007: Start of 6-week stoppage for maintenance. Bearings in the clock's chime train and the \"great bell\" striker were replaced, for the first time since installation.<ref name=07repair>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6941611.stm| work=BBC News| title= Big Ben silenced for repair work| date=11 August 2007| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> During the maintenance the clock was driven by an [[electric motor]].<ref name=ticking>{{cite web |url=http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART134 |title=Big Ben 1859&nbsp;\u2013 2009&nbsp;\u2013 Keeping the Great Clock ticking |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=27 May 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603211836/http://www.bigben.parliament.uk/ixbin/indexplus?record=ART134| archivedate=3 June 2009 | url-status=live}}</ref> Once again, BBC Radio 4 broadcast the pips during this time. The intention was that the clock should run accurately for a further 200 years before major maintenance is again required; in fact the repairs sufficed for ten years.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ed0XwaX_fHIC| last=Brand| first=Stewart| title=The Clock of the Long Now| year=2008| location=New York| isbn=978-0-7867-2292-1| publisher=Basic Books}}</ref>\n\n17 April 2013: The bells were silenced as a mark of \"profound dignity and deep respect\" during the funeral of former Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]].<ref name=watts>{{cite news| last=Watt| first=Nicholas| title=Margaret Thatcher funeral: Big Ben to be silenced as mark of respect|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/apr/15/margaret-thatcher-big-ben-silenced| accessdate=17 May 2013| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]| date=15 April 2013| location=London}}</ref>\n\nAugust 2015: The clock was discovered to be running 7 seconds fast, and coins were removed from its pendulum to correct the error, which caused it to run slow for a time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Phipps |first=Claire |title=Clockwatchers ticked off as Big Ben's chimes run seven seconds fast  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/aug/25/clockwatchers-ticked-off-as-big-bens-chimes-run-six-seconds-fast |date=25 August 2015 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n21 August 2017: Start of 4-year silencing of the chimes during maintenance and repair work to the clock mechanism, and repairs and improvements to the clock tower building. During this time, dials, hands, and lights will be removed for restoration, with at least one dial\u2014with hands driven by an electric motor\u2014left intact, functioning, and visible at any given time. Plans also include installing a lift.<ref name=BBC20170814>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40922169| work=BBC News| location=London| title=Big Ben's bongs to fall silent until 2021 for repairs| date=14 August 2017| accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> The bells, however, will still chime for events such as New Year's Eve and [[Remembrance Sunday|Remembrance Day]].<ref name=afppfp>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/big-ben-silent-bell-four-years-mps-commons-westminster-parliament-renovation-repairs-a7904056.html| title=MPs are gathering outside Big Ben to watch it bong for the final time| date=21 August 2017| newspaper=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/big-ben-will-still-bong-for-new-years-eve-and-remembrance-day-despite-four-year-silence-a3616481.html| title=Big Ben WILL still bong for New Year's Eve and Remembrance Day| newspaper=London Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\n== Bells ==\n\n=== Great Bell ===\n<!--[[Template:Bells]] and [[Big Ben bell]] redirect directly here.-->\n[[File:big-ben-1858.jpg|thumb|The second \"Big Ben\" (centre) and the Quarter Bells from ''[[News of the World|The Illustrated News of the World]]'', 4 December 1858]]\n\nThe main bell, officially known as the ''Great Bell'' but better known as ''Big Ben'', is the largest bell in the tower and part of the Great Clock of Westminster.<ref name=\"greatbell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/building-clock-tower/great-bell/| title=The Great Bell \u2013 Big Ben| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> It sounds an E-natural.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ben |url=https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-information-office/Big-Ben.pdf |date=2012 |website=House of Commons |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original bell was a 16&nbsp;[[long ton|ton]] (16.3-[[tonne]]) hour bell, cast on 6 August 1856 in [[Stockton-on-Tees]] by [[John Warner & Sons]].<ref name=wbfbb /> It is thought that the bell was originally to be called ''Victoria'' or ''Royal Victoria'' in honour of Queen Victoria, but that an MP suggested the bell's current nickname of \"Big Ben\" during a Parliamentary debate; the comment is not recorded in [[Hansard]].<ref name=icons>{{cite web |url=http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/big-ben/features/how-did-big-ben-get-its-name |last=ICONS England |title=Big Ben&nbsp;\u2013 How did Big Ben get its Name? |work=Icons of England| accessdate=30 April 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124034508/http://www.icons.org.uk/theicons/collection/big-ben/features/how-did-big-ben-get-its-name |archivedate=24 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince the tower was not yet finished, the bell was mounted in [[Palace of Westminster#Grounds|New Palace Yard]] but, during testing it cracked beyond repair and a replacement had to be made. The bell was recast on 10 April 1858 at the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] as a 13{{sfrac|1|2}}&nbsp;ton (13.76-tonne) bell.<ref name=wbfbb /><ref>The actual weight quoted by the founders is 13&nbsp; [[Long ton|tons]] 10&nbsp;[[hundredweight|cwts]] 3&nbsp;[[Avoirdupois#British adaptation|qtrs]] 15&nbsp;[[Pound (mass)|lbs]].</ref> The second bell was transported from the foundry to the tower on a trolley drawn by sixteen horses, with crowds cheering its progress; it was then pulled {{convert|200|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} up to the Clock Tower's belfry, a feat that took 18 hours. It is {{convert|7|ft|6|in|m|2}} tall and {{convert|9|ft|m|2}} diameter. This new bell first chimed in July 1859; in September it too cracked under the hammer. According to the foundry's manager, George Mears, the horologist Denison had used a hammer more than twice the maximum weight specified.<ref name=wbfbb /> For three years Big Ben was taken out of commission and the hours were struck on the lowest of the quarter bells until it was repaired. To make the repair, a square piece of metal was chipped out from the rim around the crack, and the bell given an eighth of a turn so the new hammer struck in a different place.<ref name=wbfbb /> Big Ben has chimed with a slightly different tone ever since, and is still in use today with the crack unrepaired. Big Ben was the largest bell in the British Isles until \"Great Paul\", a 16{{sfrac|3|4}}&nbsp;ton (17&nbsp;tonne) bell currently hung in [[St Paul's Cathedral]], was cast in 1881.<ref name=paul>{{cite web|url=http://www.inloughborough.com/local%20history/Great_Paul.shtml| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930141731/http://www.inloughborough.com/local%20history/Great_Paul.shtml| url-status=dead| archive-date=30 September 2007| title=The History of Great Paul| publisher=Bell foundry museum, Leicester| accessdate=19 October 2008| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Chimes ===\n[[File:BBC World Service Big Ben 1-1-2009.ogg|thumb|left|A recording from the [[BBC World Service]] radio station of the [[Westminster Chimes]] and the twelve strikes of Big Ben, as broadcast at midnight, New Year's Day 2009.]]\n\nAlong with the Great Bell, the [[Belfry (architecture)|belfry]] houses four [[quarter bells]] which play the ''[[Westminster Quarters]]'' on the quarter hours. The four quarter bells sound G{{music|sharp}}, F{{music|sharp}}, E, and B. They were cast by John Warner & Sons at their Crescent Foundry in 1857 (G{{music|sharp}}, F{{music|sharp}} and B) and 1858 (E). The Foundry was in Jewin Crescent, in what is now known as [[Barbican Centre|The Barbican]], in the City of London.<ref>{{cite news| title=The New Houses of Parliament| date=16 November 1855| work=[[Evening Standard#History|The Standard]] |page=2|location=London}}</ref> The bells are sounded by hammers pulled by cables coming from the link room\u2014a low-ceiling space between the clock room and the belfry\u2014where mechanisms translate the movement of the quarter train into the sounding of the individual bells.<ref>{{cite book |last=McKay |first=Chris |title=Big Ben: the Great Clock and the Bells at the Palace of Westminster |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r5V4HUiKRCUC&pg=SA2-PA47 |date=27 May 2010 |at=2.47\u201348 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-958569-4 |access-date=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Big Ben 2001-06-27.jpg|thumb|Big Ben]]\n\nThe quarter bells play a once-repeating, 20-note sequence of rounds and four [[Change ringing|changes]] in the key of [[E major]]: 1\u20134 at quarter past, 5\u201312 at half past, 13\u201320 and 1\u20134 at quarter to, and 5\u201320 on the hour (which sounds 25 seconds before the main bell tolls the hour). Because the low bell (B) is struck twice in quick succession, there is not enough time to pull a hammer back, and it is supplied with two wrench hammers on opposite sides of the bell. The tune is that of the [[Cambridge Chimes]], first used for the chimes of [[Church of St Mary the Great, Cambridge|Great St Mary]]'s church, [[Cambridge]], and supposedly a [[Variation (music)|variation]], attributed to [[William Crotch]], based on violin [[Phrase (music)|phrases]] from the air \"[[Messiah Part III#Part III|I know that my Redeemer liveth]]\" in [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s ''[[Messiah (Handel)|Messiah]]''.<ref name=phillips>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Alan |title=The Story of Big Ben |year=1959 |publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office |page=13}}</ref><ref name=starmer>{{cite book |last=Starmer |first=William Wooding |title=Quarter Chimes and Chime Tunes |year=1910 |location=London |publisher=Novello |pages=6\u20138}}</ref> The notional words of the chime, again derived from Great St Mary's and in turn an allusion to [[Psalm 37]]:23\u201324, are: \"All through this hour/Lord be my guide/And by Thy power/No foot shall slide\". They are written on a plaque on the wall of the clock room.<ref name=milmo>{{cite news| last=Milmo| first=Cahel| title=Bong! A change of tune at Westminster| work=The Independent| date=5 June 2006|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/bong-a-change-of-tune-at-westminster-481163.html| accessdate=8 April 2008| location=London}}</ref><ref name=lockyer>{{cite book| last=Lockyer| first=Herbert| title=A Devotional Commentary on Psalms| publisher=Kregel Christian Books| date=1 January 1993| location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=08MSVzXA_Z8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=A+devotional+commentary+on+psalms#v=onepage&q=westminster| isbn=978-0-8254-9742-1| page=149}}</ref>\n\nOne of the requirements for the clock was that the first stroke of the hour bell should be correct to within one second per day. The tolerance is with reference to [[Greenwich Mean Time]] ([[British Summer Time|BST]] in summer).<ref name=Bong /><ref>Steve Jaggs, Keeper of the Clock, interviewed on ''Sky News'', 26 April 2016.</ref><ref name=whitechapel>{{cite web| publisher=Whitechapel Bell Foundry| title=The Story of Big Ben|url=http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/bigben.htm| accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> So, at twelve o'clock, for example, it is the first of the twelve hour-bell strikes that signifies the hour (the New Year on New Year's Eve at midnight). The time signalled by the last of the \"six pips\" ([[UTC]]) may be fractionally different.\n\n== Nickname ==\nThe origin of the nickname ''Big Ben'' is the subject of some debate. The nickname was applied first to the Great Bell; it may have been named after [[Benjamin Hall, 1st Baron Llanover|Sir Benjamin Hall]], who oversaw the installation of the Great Bell, or after English heavyweight boxing champion [[Benjamin Caunt]].<ref name=wbfbb /><ref name=\"greatbell\" /><ref name=\"UKparlBB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/building-clock-tower/great-bell/| title=The Great Bell&nbsp;\u2013 Big Ben| date=13 November 2009| work=Living Heritage| publisher=UK Parliament| accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Now ''Big Ben'' is often used, by extension, to refer to the clock, the tower and the bell collectively, although the nickname is not universally accepted as referring to the clock and tower.<ref name=BigBenCOD /><ref name=Britannica>{{cite web| title=Big Ben|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/64921/Big-Ben| publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online| accessdate=27 October 2008| first=Jonathan D.| last=Betts| date=26 November 2008| work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081102173629/http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/64921/Big-Ben| archivedate=2 November 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=Columbia>{{cite web| title=Big Ben|url=http://www.bartleby.com/65/bi/BigBen.html| publisher=Columbia University Press| accessdate=27 October 2008| date=July 2001| work=The Columbia Encyclopedia| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010153226/http://www.bartleby.com/65/bi/BigBen.html| archivedate=10 October 2008| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Encarta>{{cite web |title=Big Ben |url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/dictionary_1861813060/Big_Ben.html |publisher=Microsoft Corporation |accessdate=14 January 2009 |year=2009 |work=Encarta World English Dictionary [North American Edition] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kwQ5lg9Y?url=http://uk.encarta.msn.com/dictionary_1861813060/Big_Ben.html |archivedate=31 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Some authors of works about the tower, clock and bell sidestep the issue by using the words ''Big Ben'' first in the title, then going on to clarify that the subject of the book is the clock and tower as well as the bell.<ref name=macdonald>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_FuPAwAAQBAJ| last=Macdonald| first=Peter G| title=Big Ben: The Bell, The Clock And The Tower| date=25 January 2005| location=Stroud, Gloucestershire| isbn=978-0-7524-9549-1}}</ref><ref name=Lockhart>{{cite book| last=Lockhart| first=Ann| title=Big Ben and the Westminster Clock Tower| date=1997| location=Stroud, Gloucestershire| isbn=978-0-85372-839-9}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, [[Satire|satirical]] news site [[The Rochdale Herald]] published a spoof article stating that the bell was to be renamed \"Massive Mohammed\". Many people mistook this for a genuine news story and were widely ridiculed on [[social media]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/17/people-actually-believed-that-big-ben-was-going-to-be-renamed-massive-mohammed-6859959/| title=People actually believed that Big Ben was going to be renamed 'Massive Mohammed'| first=Ashitha| last=Nagesh| date=17 August 2017| newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]| location=London| access-date=23 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/stephaniemcneal/massive-mohammed| title=This Fake Story Claiming Big Ben Will Be Renamed For Muslims Is Making A Lot of People Mad| work=[[BuzzFeed]]| access-date=23 August 2017| language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/big-ben-renamed-massive-mohammed-fake-news-parody-article-spoof-site-7900861| title=Someone joked that Big Ben would be renamed Massive Mohammed and people were furious| date=18 August 2017| work=[[Indy100]]| access-date=23 August 2017| language=en-GB}}</ref> This even inspired the creation of two online [[petition]]s.\n\n== Cultural significance ==\n[[File:Whitehall Street Traffic.jpg|thumb|[[Double-decker bus]]es frame a busy [[Whitehall]] with Big Ben in the background.]]\n\nThe clock has become a [[Culture of the United Kingdom|cultural symbol of the United Kingdom]], particularly in the visual media. When a television or film-maker wishes to indicate a generic location in the country, a popular way to do so is to show an image of the tower, often with a [[AEC Routemaster|red double-decker bus]] or [[black cab]] in the foreground.<ref name=patterson>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=John |title=City Light |url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/filmandmusic/story/0,,2091939,00.html |date=1 June 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618191946/http://arts.guardian.co.uk/filmandmusic/story/0%2C%2C2091939%2C00.html |archive-date=18 June 2008 |location=London |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=26 December 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a survey of 2,000 people found that the tower was the most popular landmark in the United Kingdom.<ref name=landmark>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/7337319.stm| work=BBC News| title=Big Ben 'UK's favourite landmark'| date=9 April 2008| accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> It has also been named as the most iconic [[London in film|film location in London]].<ref name=iconic>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/2007/10/21/big-ben-most-iconic-london-film-location-385597| newspaper=Metro| title=Big Ben most iconic London film location| date=21 October 2007| location=London| accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Big Ben illuminated.jpg|thumb|left|Big Ben's dials and belfry are illuminated at night.]]\n\nThe sound of the clock chiming has also been used this way in audio media, but as the Westminster Quarters are heard from other clocks and other devices, the sound is by no means unique. Big Ben is a focal point of [[New Year's Eve#England|New Year celebrations in the United Kingdom]], with radio and television stations airing its chimes to welcome the start of the New Year. To welcome in 2012, the clock tower was lit with fireworks that exploded at every toll of Big Ben.<ref name=welcome2012>{{cite web| title=Fireworks going off at the London Eye and Big Ben to welcome 2012 in London|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q1yLRK2M8YQ |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> Similarly, on [[Remembrance Day]], the chimes of Big Ben are broadcast to mark the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month and the start of the two minutes' silence.<ref name=remembrance>{{cite news |title=Remembrance Day across the UK |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4010971.stm |work=BBC News |date=14 November 2004 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> The chimes of Big Ben have also been used at the state funerals of monarchs on three occasions: firstly, at the [[funeral of King Edward VII]] in 1910, when Big Ben chimed 68 times, one stroke for each year of the monarch's life; secondly, at the funeral of King George V in 1936 (70 strokes); and finally, at the funeral of King George VI in 1952 (56 strokes).<ref>{{cite book|authors=[[Ben Weinreb|Weinreb, Ben]] and [[Christopher Hibbert|Hibbert, Christopher]]|title=The London Encyclopaedia|edition=reprint|page=66|year=1992|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|title-link=The London Encyclopaedia}}</ref>\n\nLondoners who live an appropriate distance from the tower and Big Ben can, by means of listening to the chimes both live and on analogue radio, hear the bell strike thirteen times. This is possible because the electronically transmitted chimes arrive virtually instantaneously, while the \"live\" sound is delayed travelling through the air since the [[speed of sound]] is relatively slow.<ref name=strike13>{{cite news |title=How to make Big Ben's clock strike 13 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11684375 |work=BBC News |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[ITN]]'s ''[[ITV News at Ten|News at Ten]]'' opening sequence formerly featured an image of the tower with the sound of Big Ben's chimes punctuating the announcement of the news headlines of the day.<ref name=robinson>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/oct/22/itv-news-at-ten-big-ben| newspaper=The Guardian| title=ITV to drop Big Ben from News at Ten titles| first=James| last=Robinson| date=22 October 2009| accessdate=13 August 2012| location=London}}</ref> The Big Ben chimes (known within ITN as \"The Bongs\") continue to be used during the headlines and all [[ITV News]] bulletins use a graphic based on the Westminster clock dial. Big Ben can also be heard striking the hour before some news bulletins on BBC Radio 4 (6 p.m. and midnight, plus 10&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays) and the BBC World Service, a practice that began on 31 December 1923. The sound of the chimes is sent live from a microphone permanently installed in the tower and connected by line to [[Broadcasting House]].<ref name=\"microphone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/0plchBL6QIaFgEmPi5PzdA |title=Big Ben Microphone |publisher=BBC |access-date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the close of the polls for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] the results of the national exit poll were projected onto the south side of the tower.<ref name=2010election>{{cite web| title=General election results beamed onto Big Ben |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2010/05/big-ben-projections/ |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=30 April 2016| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111152210/http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2010/05/big-ben-projections/| archivedate= 11 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On 27 July 2012, starting at 8:12 a.m, Big Ben chimed 30 times, to welcome the [[2012 Summer Olympics|Games of the 30th Olympiad]], which officially began that day, to London.<ref>{{cite web| title=Big Ben rings in Olympic Morning| work=[[ITV News]]| publisher=YouTube| date=27 July 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4TKKZsMl9Dg | accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== 2017 renovation ==\n[[File:Big Ben Covered in Scaffolding.jpg|thumb|Scaffolding was put up in 2017.]]\n\nOn 21 August 2017, Big Ben's chimes were silenced for four years to allow essential restoration work to be carried out on the tower. The decision to silence the bells was made to protect the hearing of the workers on the tower, and drew much criticism from senior [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] and the then Prime Minister [[Theresa May]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/16/theresa-may-says-cant-right-big-ben-besilent-four-years/|title=Theresa May says 'it can't be right for Big Ben to be silent for four years'|last=Hughes|first=Laura|date=2017-08-16|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The striking and tolling of the bells for important occasions, such as New Year's Eve and Remembrance Sunday, will be handled via an electric motor; and at least one of the four clock faces will remain visible during the restoration. Scaffolding was put up around the tower immediately after the bells were silenced. The original cost of the project to the taxpayers and creditors was estimated to be roughly \u00a329 million, but this was then more than doubled, to \u00a369 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41444415|title=Big Ben tower repair costs double|date=2017-09-29|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> In February 2020 it was confirmed that the renovations had revealed that the Elizabeth Tower had sustained greater damage than originally thought in the May 1941 bombing raid that destroyed the adjacent House of Commons. Other costly discoveries included [[asbestos]] in the belfry, the \"extensive\" use of lead paint, broken glass on the clock dials, and serious deterioration to the tower's intricate stone carvings due to air pollution.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite article| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/13/asbestos-and-damage-discovery-inflates-big-ben-repair-bill-to-80m| title=Wartime bomb damage and asbestos inflates Big Ben repair bill to \u20a480m| author=Rajeev Syal| publisher=The Guardian| date=2020-02-13| access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> The cost of addressing the new problems was estimated at \u20a418.6 million, bringing the total budget for restoring the Elizabeth Tower to nearly \u20a480 million.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The additional renovation work was not set to derail the completion of the project: Big Ben will resume its usual striking and tolling in 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40922169|title=Big Ben's bongs to fall silent until 2021|date=2017-08-14|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe aim of the renovation is to repair and conserve the tower, upgrading facilities as necessary, and ensuring the tower's integrity for future generations. The last significant renovation work to the tower was carried out in 1983\u201385. The {{convert|96|m|adj=on}} high structure is exposed to the elements, resulting in cracks and other damage to the masonry and rust damage to the ironwork. The 2,567 cast-iron roof tiles will be removed and replaced, and a lift will be installed to make access easier, along with a basic washroom with running water. The Ayrton Light at the top of the tower, which is lit when Parliament is sitting, will also be fully dismantled and restored with the other lights in the Belfry, the lights being replaced with low energy [[Light-emitting diode|LEDs]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36138203|title=Big Ben to be silenced for \u00a329m refit|date=2016-04-26|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> One of the most visible changes to the tower will be the restoration of the clock-face framework to its original colour of [[Prussian blue]], used when the tower was first built in 1859, with the black paint used to cover up the soot-stained dial frames being stripped away. The clock faces are also to be regilded, and the shields of St George are to be repainted in their original red and white colours. The 1,296 pieces of glass that make up the clock faces are also to be removed and replaced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonist.com/london/news/big-ben-goes-blue|title=Big Ben Has Been Repainted Blue|date=2019-03-21|website=Londonist|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/elizabeth-tower-and-big-ben-conservation-works-2017-/elizabeth-tower-conservation-contract-awarded/|title=Elizabeth Tower contract awarded \u2013 News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|London}}\n* [[Big Ben Aden]]\n* [[Little Ben]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|1=\"Big Ben\"|display=Big Ben|d=Q37733713|voy=Westminster|n=no|b=no|v=no|q=no}}\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/bigben Official website of Big Ben] at UK Parliament\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/ The Palace of Westminster] at UK Parliament\n* [http://www.whitechapelbellfoundry.co.uk/bigben.htm Big Ben] at Whitechapel Bell Foundry\n* [http://www.houghtonlespring.org.uk/articles/big_ben_clapper.htm Big Ben's Clapper] at Houghton-le-Spring Heritage Society\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/uk_parliament/tags/bigben Interior photos of  the tower] at UK Parliament's [[Flickr]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071012110834/http://www.raeng.org.uk/news/publications/list/lectures/Two_Towers_Lecture.pdf \"A tale of Two Towers: Big Ben and Pisa\"]\u2014transcript of a lecture by Prof. [[John Burland]]\n\n=== Videos ===\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Elffjsjbio ''The Mechanical Genius of Big Ben'' (2017)] documentary by [[Discovery (UK and Ireland)|Discovery]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZukDFfy5cnc ''Big Ben's a Hundred'' (1959)] newsreel by [[British Path\u00e9]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XtV-G2P0A74 ''Big Ben's Clean Up'' (1955)] by British Path\u00e9\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y88TCW11SHM ''Big Ben'' (1948)] by British Path\u00e9\n\n{{Bells}}\n{{London landmarks}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Bell towers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Clock towers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in London]]\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1859]]\n[[Category:Inclined towers]]\n[[Category:Individual clocks in England]]\n[[Category:National government buildings in London]]\n[[Category:Palace of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 1859]]\n[[Category:Towers in London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the City of Westminster]]\n", "name_user": "46.208.54.46", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGreat Bell)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Ben"}
{"title_page": "Ava Max", "text_new": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Ava Max\n| image            = Ava Max meeting fans (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Max meeting fans in [[Australia]] after her appearance on ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' in April 2019\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Amanda Koci<!-- Do not change birth name to full name; stated in the article she changed it when she was 13 --><ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/02/sweet-but-psycho-ava-max-interview|title=\u201cSweet but Psycho\u201d Singer Ava Max Is Trying to \"Bring Pop Back\"|last=Duboff|first=Josh|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=February 13, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1994|2|16}}<ref name=Allmusic/>\n| birth_place      = [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web |last=Frometa |first=RJ |title=Ava Max Returns with New Single 'Sweet but Psycho' |url=http://ventsmagazine.com/2018/08/17/ava-max-returns-with-new-single-sweet-but-psycho |website=Vents |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |date=August 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927170557/http://ventsmagazine.com/2018/08/17/ava-max-returns-with-new-single-sweet-but-psycho/ |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|piano}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[dance-pop]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Atlantic Records Ava Max |url=http://www.atlanticrecords.com/artists/ava-max |access-date=September 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927085646/http://www.atlanticrecords.com/artists/ava-max |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| associated_acts  = [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]\n| website          = {{url|avamax.com}}\n| alias            = * AVA\n* Ava Koci\n}}\n\n'''Amanda Ava Koci''' (born '''Amanda Koci'''<!-- Do not change birth name to full name; stated in the article she changed it when she was 13 -->; February 16, 1994),<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/> known professionally as '''Ava Max''', is an American singer and songwriter. The single \"[[Sweet but Psycho]]\" became her breakthrough song when it topped the charts in 26 countries including the UK, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Sweden, and New Zealand, while also reaching the top 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |last=DeVille |first=Chris |title=Can Ava Max\u2019s Global Hit 'Sweet But Psycho' Take Over America Too? |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2029230/sweet-but-psycho-ava-max/franchises/the-week-in-pop/ |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=January 25, 2019 |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8513170/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-hot-100-number-one-eighth-week|title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Rules Billboard Hot 100 for Eighth Week, Ava Max's 'Sweet but Psycho' Hits Top 10|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=May 28, 2019|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The follow-up singles \"[[So Am I (Ava Max song)|So Am I]]\", \"[[Torn (Ava Max song)|Torn]]\" and \"[[Salt (Ava Max song)|Salt]]\" were released in 2019. Ava Max is known for her signature hair style, dubbed the \"Max Cut\".<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nAmanda Ava Koci was born Amanda Koci<!-- Do not change birth name to full name; stated in the article she changed it when she was 13 --> on February 16, 1994, in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], to [[Albanians|Albanian]] parents from [[Tirana]] and [[Sarand\u00eb]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=AvaMax|number=1061070044870791173|date=November 10, 2018|title=Tirana and Sarande|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kos\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Ava-Max-Takes-Control-With-New-Single-My-Way-20180501|title=Ava Max Takes Control With New Single 'My Way'|author=BWW News Desk|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|accessdate=October 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927124938/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Ava-Max-Takes-Control-With-New-Single-My-Way-20180501|archive-date=September 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She has described herself as \"100% Albanian\" and stated that she \"definitely wants to give back to the Albanian community when [she] can\".<ref name=\"BelfastTelegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/features/ava-max-my-parents-left-albania-in-1990-and-lived-in-a-church-in-paris-for-a-whole-year-37700264.html|title=Ava Max: My parents left Albania in 1990 and lived in a church in Paris for a whole year|date=January 11, 2019|publisher=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref> She moved with her family to [[Virginia]] when she was 8 years old,<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/> where she competed in numerous singing competitions before she entered high school.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rowlands|first=Geoffrey|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/617395/Sweet-But-Psycho-makes-Ava-a-star|title=Sweet But Psycho makes Ava a star|website=[[Gulf Times]]|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref> When she was 13, she came up with the middle name \"Ava\" which she adopted as her first name, claiming that \"I never felt like an Amanda\". At age 14, she moved with her mother to [[Los Angeles]], in pursuit of a career in music. She found the city to be \"overwhelming\". She went back to Virginia a year later, stating that she was grateful for the return because it allowed for \"a normal childhood\",<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/> eventually moving back to Los Angeles when she was 17.<ref name=Idolator2019>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7687574/ava-max-sweet-but-psycho-interview?ios=1&safari=1|title=Ava Max On \"Sweet But Psycho\" & Making Pop Fun Again: Interview|first=Mike|last=Wass|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2013\u20132017: Career beginnings ===\n{{quote box\n| width = 25%\n| align = right\n| quote = It was funny, \u2019cause I was actually experimenting with different haircuts and colors, pink hair, blue hair, all that kind of stuff. Nothing felt like me. One day I cut my hair, my actual hair, cut it on the right side, and I remember I had something in the oven; I think they were chocolate-chip cookies. And I run downstairs without cutting the other side. I run downstairs, and then I\u2019m like, \u2018Oh my God, [the cookies] almost burnt.\u2019 As I\u2019m going [back] upstairs, I see in the mirror my reflection and the haircut, and...I literally tilted my head, like, why does this feel like me? It felt like me, like I had found myself.\n| source = \u2014 Ava Max on her signature \"Max Cut\"<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/>\n}}\nUnder the stage name Ava, her debut song \"Take Away the Pain\" was published in May 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://de.napster.com/artist/ava-indie-pop/album/take-away-the-pain|title=Take Away the Pain|publisher=|via=de.napster.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R-LyMnl94vI|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610004431/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R-LyMnl94vI|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2013|title=AVA - Take Away the Pain (Official Music Video) - YouTube|date=10 June 2013}}</ref> and in July 2015, the Canadian DJ and producer duo [[Project 46]] released a remixed version of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOq1UTHyj5w|title=Project 46 - Take Away The Pain (feat. Ava Koci) [Cover Art]|first=|last=Ultra Music|date=16 July 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> After years of having demos rejected from record producers and songwriters, she met record producer [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]] at a dinner party in 2014 in LA where she sang \"[[Happy Birthday to You|Happy Birthday]]\" to him.<ref name=Idolator2019/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/after-working-with-dr-luke-cirkut-breaks-out-on-his-own.html|title=After Working With Dr. Luke, Cirkut Breaks Out on His Own|first=Myles|last=Tanzer|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref> According to Max, they \"opened up a lot of doors\" together,<ref name=Idolator2019/> and in July 2016, she released \"Anyone but You\", one of many songs she worked on with Cirkut, on [[SoundCloud]].<ref name=\"soundcloud.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/avamax/anyone-but-you|title=Anyone But You|publisher=|via=soundcloud.com}}</ref> The song gained traction and attracted the attention of various record labels that contacted her through email, ultimately leading her to sign a record deal with [[Atlantic Records]].<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/><ref name=Idolator2019/>\n\nAfter signing the deal, she began searching for a last name to use as her stage name. In an interview with ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', Max described how she formulated her stage name:<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/><blockquote>Max came about because it felt very masculine, and I feel a little masculine sometimes, like 50/50, like my hair. I wanted something with the feminine that Ava has, and Max has masculinity, so I added those two together.</blockquote> During 2017, Max adopted her signature hair style, dubbed the \"Max Cut\", which can be seen in her logo.<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/> It consists of the right side of her hair chopped as a [[bob cut]], with the left side long and loose.<ref name=\"AvaMaxVanityFair\"/>\n\n=== 2018\u2013present: Breakthrough ===\n[[File:Ava Max at the Rix FM Festival in Gothenburg (48534754301) (cropped).jpg|thumb|150px|right|Ava Max performing at the Gothenburg Rix FM Festival in 2019]]\nIn April 2018, \"My Way\" was released,<ref>{{cite web |title=Ava Max Takes Control With New Single 'My Way' |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Ava-Max-Takes-Control-With-New-Single-My-Way-20180501 |website=Broadway World |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927124938/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Ava-Max-Takes-Control-With-New-Single-My-Way-20180501 |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> which reached a peak of 38 on the Romanian [[Airplay 100 (Romania)|Airplay 100]] chart.<ref name=\"Romania\">Peaks in Romania:\n* \"My Way\": {{cite news|url=https://www.unsitedemuzica.ro/topuri/Top-Airplay-100-Matthew-Koma-ramane-regele-clasamentului-p5437|title=Top Airplay 100 \u2013 Matthew Koma r\u0103m\u00e2ne regele clasamentului|trans-title=Top Airplay 100 \u2013 Matthew Koma remains the king of the chart|language=Romanian|author=Arvunescu, Victor|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=June 18, 2018|publisher=Un site de muzic\u0103}}\n* \"Sweet but Psycho\": {{cite web|url=http://www.kissfm.ro/podcasturi/5944|title=Airplay 100 \u2013 16 decembrie 2018|publisher=[[Kiss FM (Romania)|Kiss FM]]|language=Romanian|accessdate=December 17, 2018|date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, \"Slippin\", a collaboration with [[Gashi (rapper)|Gashi]], was released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ava Max Releases 'Slippin' Featuring GASHI |url=https://the360mag.com/ava-max-releases-slippin-featuring-gashi |website=360 |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927165137/https://the360mag.com/ava-max-releases-slippin-featuring-gashi/ |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Ava Max Track 'Slippin'\u2019 Featuring Gashi |url=https://newmusicweekly.com/new-ava-max-track-slippin-featuring-gashi |website=[[New Music Weekly]] |access-date=2018-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127223047/https://newmusicweekly.com/new-ava-max-track-slippin-featuring-gashi |archive-date=2018-11-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ava Max lo hace a su manera |url=http://www.billboard.com.ar/noticia/5532/ava-max-lo-hace-a-su-manera |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927085716/http://www.billboard.com.ar/noticia/5532/ava-max-lo-hace-a-su-manera |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, she featured on \"Into Your Arms\" by American rapper Witt Lowry. A month later, \"[[Salt (Ava Max song)|Salt]]\" appeared on [[SoundCloud]]. In August 2018, she released \"Not Your Barbie Girl\" as a [[promotional single]].\n\n\"[[Sweet but Psycho]]\" was released on August 17, 2018. The song became Max's commercial breakthrough, reaching number one in more than 26 countries including Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Norway, Sweden, New Zealand and the United Kingdom, where it stayed at number one for four consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Who is Ava Max? The Sweet But Psycho star soaring up the charts |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/who-is-ava-max-the-sweet-but-psycho-star-soaring-up-the-charts__24768 |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |date=November 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Watch Ava Max's Video for 'Sweet but Psycho'|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/VIDEO-Watch-Ava-Maxs-Video-for-Sweet-but-Psycho-20180827 |website=[[BroadwayWorld]] |accessdate=September 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927085741/https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/VIDEO-Watch-Ava-Maxs-Video-for-Sweet-but-Psycho-20180827|archive-date=September 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, the song reached the top of the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart and later reached top 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"Trust\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8513170/lil-nas-x-old-town-road-hot-100-number-one-eighth-week|title=Lil Nas X's 'Old Town Road' Rules Billboard Hot 100 for Eighth Week, Ava Max's 'Sweet but Psycho' Hits Top 10|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=May 28, 2019|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> Max was also featured on [[David Guetta|David Guetta's]] album ''[[7 (David Guetta album)|7]]'', on the track \"Let It Be Me\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Pandora Predictions to Know: Flora Cash, Social House, Ava Max & Summer Walker |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8475032/pandora-predictions-flora-cash-social-house-ava-max |website=Billboard |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927075253/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8475032/pandora-predictions-flora-cash-social-house-ava-max |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2019, she released the follow-up single \"[[So Am I (Ava Max song)|So Am I]]\", which reached the top 10 and 20 in several countries. The songs \"Blood, Sweat & Tears\" and \"Freaking Me Out\" were simultaneously released in July 2019 as promotional singles.<ref name=\"bst\"/><ref name=\"fmo\"/>\n\nIn August 2019, Max was featured on the song \"Slow Dance\" by American singer-songwriter [[AJ Mitchell]],<ref name=\"ajm\"/> and released \"[[Torn (Ava Max song)|Torn]]\" as a single later that month. On September 4, 2019, she entered a joint co-publishing deal with [[Warner Chappell Music]] and Artist Publishing Group, stating \"I\u2019m someone who speaks my mind, so it was important to me that my publisher value originality and creative expression.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/publishing/8529123/ava-max-co-publishing-warner-chappell-apg|title=Ava Max Signs Joint Co-Publishing Agreement With Warner Chappell and APG|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Atkinson|first=Katie|date=September 4, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> On October 31, 2019, she released a music video for the promotional single \"Freaking Me Out\" as a Halloween special.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Ava-Max-Release-Freaking-Me-Out-Music-Video-20191031|title=Ava Max Release 'Freaking Me Out' Music Video|author=TV News Desk|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|date=October 31, 2019|access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3AKPaq0IaDk|title=Ava Max - Freaking Me Out [Official Music Video]|via=[[YouTube]]|date=October 31, 2019|access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> Max won best [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best Push Act|Best Push Act]] at the [[2019 MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8542367/mtv-emas-2019-winners-list|title=Here Are All the Winners From the 2019 MTV EMAs|author=Billboard Staff|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 4, 2019|access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref> On November 6, 2019, a duet called \"[[Tab\u00fa (song)|Tab\u00fa]]\" between Max and [[Pablo Albor\u00e1n]] was released.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4O7HQboUEl/|title=#TAB\u00da 6 \u2022 NOV \u2022 19|via=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref> The previously released song \"Salt\" was sent to digital streaming platforms on December 12, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8546157/ava-max-salt-listen|title=Ava Max Finally Drops Fan Favorite Song 'Salt'|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 12, 2019|access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Max collaborated with British-Norwegian DJ and record producer [[Alan Walker (music producer)|Alan Walker]] on the song \"[[Alone, Pt. II]]\", which was released on December 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cultr.com/news/alan-walker-to-release-alone-pt-ii-with-ava-max-on-27th/|title=Alan Walker To Release 'Alone, Pt. II' With Ava Max On 27th|last=Tryon|first=Oliver|website=Cultr|date=24 December 2019|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> \"On Somebody\" was released as a promotional single on December 30, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Ava-Max-Releases-On-Somebody-20191230|title=Ava Max Releases 'On Somebody'|last=|first=|date=December 30, 2019|website=BroadwayWorld|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, 2020, Max released \"[[Kings & Queens (Ava Max song)|Kings & Queens]]\" as the lead single from her upcoming debut album.<ref name=\"MTV\"/>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\nMax has been labeled as a [[Pop music|pop]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Pop Singer Ava Max Scores Her First U.K. No. 1 Single With 'Sweet But Psycho'|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2018/12/29/pop-singer-ava-max-scores-her-first-u-k-no-1-single-with-sweet-but-psycho/|first=Hugh|last=McIntyre|website=[[Forbes]]|date=December 29, 2018|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> and [[dance-pop]]<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|title=Ava Max Biography, Albums, Streaming Links|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ava-max-mn0003655084|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Neil Z.|last=Yeung|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> singer. She grew up listening to artists such as [[Celine Dion]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Fugees]],<ref name=\"BillboardInfluence\">{{cite web |title=Ava Max Talks 'Mind-Blowing' Rise of 'Sweet but Psycho,' Debut Album Plans & Why 'No One's Better' Than Beyonce|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/podcasts/8505351/ava-max-interview-sweet-but-psycho-album-pop-shop-podcast |website=Billboard|last1=Atkinson|first1=Katie|last2=Caulfield|first2=Keith |date=April 2, 2019|access-date=April 2, 2019}}</ref> [[Mariah Carey]], and [[Whitney Houston]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Ava Max perform 'Sweet but Psycho' on TODAY |url=https://www.today.com/video/watch-ava-max-perform-sweet-but-psycho-on-today-1431855683559 |website=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]|date=January 26, 2019|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> She has also cited [[Beyonc\u00e9]],<ref name=\"BillboardInfluence\"/> [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Gwen Stefani]], [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]], [[Britney Spears]], [[Christina Aguilera]], and [[Lady Gaga]] as some of her influences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ava Max Explains the Meaning Behind her Hit 'Sweet but Psycho' |url=https://www.warnermusic.co.nz/news/ava-max-explains-the-meaning-behind-sweet-but-psycho |publisher=[[Warner Music New Zealand]] |access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> Max has been compared to Gaga for her music and \"ostentatious presentation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7721705/ava-max-addresses-lady-gaga-comparisons-huge-compliment|title=Ava Max Addresses Lady Gaga Comparisons: \"It's A Huge Compliment\"|last=Wass|first=Mike|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=March 13, 2019|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2029230/sweet-but-psycho-ava-max/franchises/the-week-in-pop/|title=Can Ava Max's Global Hit \"Sweet But Psycho\" Take Over America Too?|last=DeVille|first=Chris|website=[[Stereogum]]|date=January 24, 2019|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> She has stated that Carey is her biggest influence, recalling how she grew up listening to her music on loop.<ref name=\"Paper\">{{cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/ava-max-kings-and-queens-interview-2645581775.html|title=Ava Max Talks Quarantine and How Khaleesi Inspired Her New Single|last=Goldfine|first=Jael|website=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAccording to a 2019 interview with ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'', Max revealed that she had been attracted to women in the past, but has chosen not to label her sexuality, stating \"Personally, I like it when it's about who you are as a person. I don't like people putting me, or anyone else I know in a box.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://attitude.co.uk/article/ava-max-wont-label-her-sexuality/22000/|title=Ava Max won't 'label' her sexuality|date=2019-10-11|website=Attitude.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Singles ===\n==== As lead artist ====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Ava-Max/chart-history/HSI|title=Ava Max Chart History - Billboard Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ava+Max|title=Discography Ava Max|website=australian-charts.com|accessdate=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Canadian Hot 100|CAN]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Ava-Max/chart-history/CAN|title=Ava Max Chart History - Canadian Hot 100|language=en|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat national de l'\u00e9dition phonographique|FRA]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ava+Max|title=Discographie Ava Max|language=fr|website=lescharts.com|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/suche?artist_search=Ava+Max&do_search=do|title=Discographie Ava Max|publisher=GfK Entertainment|accessdate=May 3, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[VG-lista|NOR]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://norwegiancharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ava+Max|title=Discography Ava Max|website=norwegiancharts.com|accessdate=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=4579|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=January 7, 2019|accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br><ref>{{cite web |title=Discography Ava Max |url=http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ava+Max |website=swedishcharts.com |accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Ava+Max|title=Discographie Ava Max|website=hitparade.ch|language=de|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/54532/ava-max/|title=Ava Max {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Sweet but Psycho]]\"\n| 2018\n| 10 || 2 || 11 || 8 || 1 || 1 || 1 || 1 || 1 || 1\n|\n* [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Sweet+But+Psycho#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]]: 5\u00d7 Platinum<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2020.htm|title=ARIA C